Commentary.Commentary: Now it is time for the Kiwi reply, their bowlers have done the job and it is now time for their batters to do their bit. Not going to be easy as it is not the ideal conditions to bat on. The question is, can the Indian bowlers capitalize? We will find out in a bit.

India will be disappointed with how they performed today. The problem for them was, they kept losing wickets at regular intervals and none of their batters went onto make most of the starts they got. Not even a single half ton. Yes, the conditions are tough but one believes, they should have gotten over the 250-run mark. Right now, they are probably a little under par.

4 wickets in the first session and three wickets in no time, within half an hour in the second session for the Kiwis. Jamieson is undoubtedly the star for them with a fifer. Everybody bowled well, Bew Zealand through will be a little disappointed with Southee but the others made up for it and Williamson will be pretty pleased after he elected to bowl.

A huge round of applause for the Kiwis as they make their way off the field. It has been an outstanding effort from them today. It was India who started today in a good position but it is the Kiwis who have their noses ahead at the moment.

OUT! TAKEN! Jadeja has been strangled down the leg side and INDIA HAVE BEEN BOWLED OUT FOR 217! Not the best of deliveries, it is down the leg side. Jadeja looks to flick, it goes off the inner half a little too fine and Watling dives to his right and takes it.
Commentary.Howout: c BJ Watling b Trent Boult

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! What a great way to get off the mark, the pressure of the hat-trick ball does not trouble Shami at all. This is full and outside off, Shami leans and slashes it through the cover region for a boundary.
Shami is the last man in. He'll be facing the bat-trick ball.

OUT! LBW! Kyle Jamieson with a 5-fer in the most important fixture. His consistency pays off. An inswinger, on middle and leg, Bumrah looks to defend it but misses. As the ball goes through and hit the pads. Kyle Jamieson and the Kiwis make a loud appeal for LBW and the umpire raises his finger in a flash. A hat-trick ball now for Jamieson.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Kyle Jamieson

Commentary.Commentary: Jasprit Bumrah walks out to bat!

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! With this Kyle Jamieson gets his fourth wicket. It is a treat to watch this lad bowl. Good length ball, outside off, Sharma moves across the stumps which make him play at it. He looks to push it through the off side, but the ball takes the outside edge and flies towards Ross Taylor at first slip, who takes the catch calmly. Eight down now the Indian team.
Commentary.Howout: c Ross Taylor b Kyle Jamieson

Commentary.Commentary: Good length ball, outside off, coming back in. Sharma leaves it watchfully.
A loud appeal for LBW turned down. Full and on off, Sharma looks to defend it but misses and gets rapped on the back pad. Missing the off stump.
BEATEN! Kyle Jamieson has been brilliant with the ball today. A full ball, outside off, nipping away. Sharma looks to defend it but misses.
Another one outside off, shaping away. Left alone. Ishant will be on strike again.
Another single! Outside off, Sharma plays it late and through point for one.
On off, Ishant walks right across and blocks it.
Outside off, left alone.
Beaten! That swung a long way. It lands around middle and then shapes away. Sharma looks to defend but is beaten. It keeps moving as it gets to the keeper who dives and collects it.
Edged but short! Really nicely played in the end! Shorter and on off, Ishant hops, rides on top of the bounce and plays it on the bounce to third slip.
Who will bowl from the other end? It is Trent Boult who comes into the attack. His figures 20-4-46-1 so far.
A dot to end then! On middle, this is pushed back to the bowler.
Really good fielding again! This is fuller and on off, Jadeja drives it square on the off side. Colin dives to his right and stops it. No single taken too.
Length yet again and outside off. Left alone nicely.
From around the wicket now goes full and outside off, left alone.
Brilliant fielding! This is fuller and on middle, it is driven nicely but the fielder at mid on dives to his right and saves at least two.
Straightaway a run for India. It is off the inner half but a single. Fuller and this one tails back in from outside off. Sharma looks to drive but it goes off the inner half towards fine leg for one.

The New Zealand fielders stride out in the middle. Followed by Ravindra Jadeja and ​​​​Ishant Sharma with their swords. Kyle Jamieson to start with the ball. Surprisingly enough, the sun is out post Lunch. Hope it stays around for a while.
...Day 3, Session 2...

Right. All about New Zealand in this session as they have ensured that the middle order of India does not trouble them much. Although, can Jadeja, help them get around the 250-run mark. Will he manage to hang around? Or will the Kiwi bowlers continue their good work? Join us at 6:10 pm IST (1240 GMT) for the second session to find out.
Jadeja has the tail with him now and India will hope he can somehow take them to a score around 230 or 240. New Zealand on the other hand, would want to finish things off quickly. Can they do so?

Jamieson got Kohli and Pant quite early in the session. Rahane also did not last long and at that time, it seemed they would be bowled out before Lunch. Ashwin and Jadeja though hung in there and took India over 200 but Ashwin too fell after that just before Lunch.
A really good session for the Kiwis. 4 wickets is what they have got and one can say they are probably on top, not by a lot but certainly on top.

A loud shout from behind the stumps for a caught behind but the umpire is unmoved.. A touch short, on the body line. Ravindra Jadeja looks to flick it but misses. But there was some sound, but not off the glove. ITS TIME FOR LUNCH ON DAY 3. INDIA END THE SESSION AT 211 for 7.
This is full and on middle, Jadeja defends it back to the bowler.
Beauty by Trent Boult. Good length ball, outside off, swinging away. A good leave by Ravindra Jadeja.
Full ball, around middle and leg, Jadeja defends it to the leg side.
Full, outside off, Jadeja drives it through covers for a couple.
Back of a length ball, on off, Jadeja is surprised by the bounce and tries to sway away from the line of the delivery, but was unable to do that. The ball clips of his chest and goes to the keeper.
Down the leg side. Left alone.
Almost drags it on! This is just outside off, Ishant is unsure whether to play at it or not. In the end, he looks to leave but it goes off the inside edge, just past the off pole.
Two! Fuller and around off, Sharma strokes it through covers for two.
Short and down the leg side, Sharma lets it be.
This is fuller and around off, it shapes away. Ishant looks to play it with a straight bat. It goes off the outside edge towards gully.
On middle, this is worked around the corner for one. A single then off the first ball. Ishant has 5 balls to face now.

DROPPED! A rare mistake in the slip cordon for New Zealand. A length ball, outside off, Jadeja looks to drive but the ball takes the outside edge and flies to Tim Southee at the slips, who is unable to hold the ball. The batters sneak a single.
Fuller and on middle, Jadeja blocks it to cover.
Full and on off, Jadeja defends it solidly.
A touch short on off, Jadeja wanted to play it initially but decides to leave it in the end.
Fullish and on off, Jadeja keeps it out solidly.
BEATEN! On a length, outside off, nipping away, Jadeja looks to defend but misses.
Good length ball, way down the leg side, into the keeper's glove.
Ishant Sharma walks out to bat now!

OUT! CAUGHT! A nice comeback by Tim Southee as he gets the better of Ashwin this time. Maybe Ashwin got carried away after that boundary. This is full and outside off, Ashwin extends his arms and decides to chase this one. But only managed to get the outside edge and Tom Latham takes yet another sharp catch at second slip. An important and helpful cameo of Ravichandran Ashwin comes to an end.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Latham b Tim Southee

Commentary.Commentary: FOUR! Ashwin looks in some fine touch now. A touch short, on off, Ashwin camps back and punches it through cover for a boundary. Moves to 22.
On off, defended solidly.
On a length, on off, Ashwin drives it through mid off for a coupl. 200 up for India. The crowd is delighted.
Good length ball, down the leg side. Ashwin looks to flick it but misses.
Full and on off, Jadeja defends it watchfully.
A length ball, down the leg side, Jadeja looks to flick but misses.
On a length, on middle, Ashwin tucks it to mid-wicket for a single.
Quicker, good length ball, outside off, Ashwin lets it go to the keeper.
On a length,  on off, Ashwin blocks it to cover.
Short of a length on middle, Ashwin pushes it back to the bowler.
Fuller and on off, Ashwin drives it down the ground, past mid off. Neil Wagner gives it a chase and was able to cut it off in time. The batters come back for three.
EDGY FOUR! Up and over the slip cordon. A length ball, nipping away, Ashwin looks to go hard at it, the ball takes the outside edge and over the slip region for a boundary at third man.
A bit of an issue with the ball. Kane Williamson showed it to the umpires after it got wet post that drive from Ashwin but the umpires are happy with it. No change.
Fullish and on off, Ashwin drives it to cover but cannot find the gap.
BEATEN! What a beauty! A length ball, on off, swinging away, Ashwin looks to drive but misses as the ball zips past the outside edge.
Full again, on middle, Jadeja clips it through mid-wicket and gets a single. Moves to 11.
Fires in a full ball, on off, Jadeja blocks it out watchfully.
FOUR! A nice way to end the over. Ashwin uses his wrists this time. A length ball, on the pads. Ashwin flicks it past mid-wicket and finds the boundary.
Fullish, on off, Ashwin works it to short mid-wicket.
A length ball, on off, Ashwin drives it through cover for a couple more.
An inswinger, attacking the stumps, Ashwin flicks it through mid-wicket for first runs. He collects two.
Back of a length ball, on off,  Ashwin goes back and defends it, but the ball takes the outside edge and lands just a few spaces in front of point.
Good length ball, outside off, Ashwin lets it go to the keeper.
Trent Boult to bowl as well. 16-4-34-1 so far.
Full toss, around off, Jadeja pushes it to mid on.
A full ball, outside off, Jadeja extends his arms and taps it down to slip cordon.
Again a carbon copy of the previous delivery, Jadeja works it towards mid-wicket.
THE SECOND NEW BALL HAS BEEN TAKEN. New Zealand have around 30 minutes to try and get it into effect.
An inswinger, full on off, Jadeja blocks it out watchfully.
Good length delivery, way outside off, Jadeja shoulders arms to it.
Southee coming around the wicket. Serves a length ball, outside off, Jadeja has no stroke to offer.
A touch short, on off, Ashwin tucks it to the leg side.
Back of a length ball, around middle and off, Ashwin blocks it back to the bowler.
Good length ball, around the hips, Ashwin tucks it to square leg.
A touch short, on off, Ashwin stays back and defends it onto the pitch.
Full, on off, Ashwin drives it to cover.
Back of a length ball, around off, Ashwin leans back and lets it go to the keeper.
On a length, outside off, this one comes back in sharply, Jadeja shoulders arms to it.
A length ball, outside off, Jadeja lets it go to the keeper.
Good length, outside off, swinging away, left alone by Jadeja.
Full and down the leg side, Jadeja looks to flick but the ball stays away. BJ Watling this time dives to his right to stop the ball.
Another, length ball, on off, nips in, Jadeja keeps it out.

BOWLED! But not out. Why? Because Ravindra Jadeja backed away at the last possible moment. Southee was just about to deliver. He delivers the ball and it hits the leg stump. Dead ball signalled. Replays show that Jadeja was looking at the ground till that moment and suddenly when he looked up, Timothy was right up, charging in.
On a length, coming back in, Jadeja blocks it out solidly.
Tim Southee finally gets a bowl. 17-4-47-0 so far.

A loud appeal for caught behind but the umpire is not interested. A full ball, down the leg side. Ashwin swings his blade but misses, as the ball goes through to the keeper, where BJ Watling dives to his left to make a top stop. The Kiwis thought there was a thin edge but nothing from the umpire.
A length ball, on middle, Ashwin looks to flick it but the ball takes the leading edge and rolls to the off side.
Ravichandran Ashwin walks in at number 8, replacing Ajinkya Rahane.

OUT! CAUGHT! Superb fielding placement by Kane Williamson and Neil Wagner. At the start of this over, Wagner sent a signal to Rahane that he was going to target bumpers at him. He kept three fielders on the leg side, two in front of square. A ball before, Rahane survived off a top edge. But he plays a similar shot almost immediately and hits it straight to Tom Latham at square leg. It is a poor shot. Because you know what is coming and it is not actually necessary to play this at this stage, given that you have just survived a ball before. Latham was got in at square leg just after that last ball and he is into action straightaway. Rahane is distraught. Wagner is pumped up. New Zealand are into the bowling all-rounders now.
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Latham b Neil Wagner

Commentary.Commentary: In the air.. Safe! Back of a length ball, outside off, Rahane looks to pull it, but does not time it well. The ball takes the top edge and flies towards mid-wicket but it lands in a vacant region. Two taken.
Full and outside off, Rahane drives it to mid off.
A low full toss, on middle, Rahane nudges it to mid-wicket.

FOUR! Well played. Full ball, on off, Jadeja leans and drives it past mid off as the ball races towards the boundary rope at long off. The camera pans to the Indian dressing room where Virat Kohli stands up and applauds that shot. Clearly, India believe the time has come to start scoring some runs.
Another length ball, outside off, Jadeja lets it go to the keeper.
On a length, way outside off, Jadeja leaves it alone.
Full and outside off. An easy leave for Ravindra Jadeja.
On a length, outside off, Rahane works it to sweeper cover for a single.

FOUR! Clipped away! There we go. Jamieson is off and the scoreboard ticks on. A nice way for India to start the post-Drinks session. A touch fuller, on the pads, Rahane clips it towards fine leg for a boundary.

DRINKS BREAK. End of a fine battling hour. 12.2 overs, 25 runs, 2 wickets. A game of attrition it has been. New Zealand have been right on the money while India are playing a game of patience. Just feel that this is the perfect stage for Ajinkya Rahane. He is at his best in the most trying conditions and he becomes crucial for India to get to 300. He has not played too many loose shots and looks in good rhythm. Kohli and Pant were kept quiet and worked over. The good thing for India is - it has been Kyle Jamieson doing all the damage and he has bowled a spell of 6-3-12-2 already. This indicates that a bowling change is around the corner and that is where the Asians will look to score. Here comes COLIN DE GRANDHOMME. 11-6-23-0 so far.
A touch fuller on off, Jadeja blocks it solidly.
BEATEN! Nicely bowled by Neil Wagner. A length ball, outside off, nips away. Jadeja looks to defend it but misses as the ball beats the outside edge.
Good length ball, outside off, swinging away. Jadeja leaves it alone.
Nice shot by Ajinkya Rahane. A full ball, on middle, Rahane removes his front leg and flicks it through mid-wicket. But the ball does not have the legs to reach the boundary. Three runs taken.
Serves a full ball, on off, Rahane defends it watchfully.
On a length, around leg, Rahane pulls it towards square leg for a couple. Good running.
Another short ball, on off, nips away, this one gets an extra bounce after hitting the deck. Good leave by Ravindra Jadeja.
Back of a length delivery, around off, Jadeja sways away from the line of the delivery.
Full, outside off, Jadeja pushes it through the cover region for a couple. Moves to 6.
On a length, outside off, swinging away, Jadeja lets it go to the keeper.
Full and outside off, Rahane leans in and drives it through covers. The batters pick three before the fielder cuts it off.
Fires in a full ball, around middle, Rahane defends it solidly.
Outside off, on a length, let through.

EDGED, FOUR! Full, outside off, swinging away, Ravindra Jadeja has a poke at it, with soft hands. The ball takes the outside edge but the soft hands prevent it from carrying to third slip. Tim Southee gets a very difficult chance to stop the ball as it lands right in front of him. Goes past his hands to the third man fence.

We always marvel about New Zealand's fielding attributes. Since the start of 2019, for a minimum of 10 Tests played, New Zealand have recorded an efficiency of 91 percent in catching. That is an efficiency of taking 9 catches out of 10. They have always been good catchers, being nimble on their feet. It was started primarily by Brendon McCullum who just redefined fielding.
Full, around middle, flicked straight to mid-wicket.
Landed outside off, swinging away, left alone.
This one swings in, Rahane flicks it towards backward square leg in the deep for a single.
Full, around off, pushed towards cover by Ajinkya Rahane.
Fuller, around off, solidly defended. Kyle Jamieson's figures read 19-12-21-3.
Around off, on a length, pushed towards point.
Ravindra Jadeja walks in at number 7, replacing Rishabh Pant.

OUT! CAUGHT AT SLIP! It is that man, Kyle Jamieson again. But this wicket is more to the fault of Rishabh Pant. Did he get carried away after that boundary? Too loose a shot. Perhaps he felt it is time to break the shackles. Full, wide outside off, Pant reaches out and looks to drive. The ball moves but the feet don't. An outside edge is taken and the ball literally flies to second slip where Tom Latham takes a very sharp catch. That was travelling. He played with tremendous self restraint, did Pant and played two bad shots in 22 balls - one took an inside edge and went to hit the pads, the other took the outside edge and had him walk back to the pavillion. Jamieson has his third!
Commentary.Howout: c Tom Latham b Kyle Jamieson

Commentary.Commentary: Around off, moving away, left alone.

FOUR! Rishabh Pant is off the mark on the 20th delivery he has faced. He has not quite middled it, but he will get a boundary. Full, outside off, Pant leans and looks to flick. Gets it off the lower part of the bat but the ball still races away through mid-wicket. Trent Boult gives it a chase from the 30-yard circle, puts in a late dive after the ball touches the ropes and comes second.
Around middle, nudged towards fine leg for a single.

On a good length, outside off, coming in, Ajinkya Rahane shoulders arms. Ahhh wait. The third umpire has indicated to Michael Gough that Jamieson has overstepped. NO BALL is signalled but replays show that it was very, very tight. It cannot be said with total conviction that the foot landed on the line. Some part of the heel seemed to be behind the line.
Full, around middle, Rishabh looks to flick but the ball swings away and goes off the leading edge towards cover. Back-to-back maiden overs.
40 balls. Number of deliveries bowled in succession without conceding a run off the bat. Tremendous discipline. Full, outside off, moving away, left alone.

Fuller, outside off, swinging away, Pant sholders arms again. He is shoing great restraint and letting balls go. He has faced 17 balls and not scored a single run but it is just a matter of time before he gets going.
Fuller, outside off, tempting to drive, Rishabh Pant holds himself back.
On middle and off, flicked straight to mid-wicket.
Full, outside off, swinging away, left alone.
Bouncer time! Here comes the first bowling change of the day. Neil Wagner it is. 10-3-28-1 so far.
Fuller, around off, defended solidly by Ajinkya. Third successive maiden by Kyle Jamieson.

That's another great delivery. Right in the channel, in the corridor of uncertainty, the avenue of apprehension, just outside off, Jinx is not sure whether to play at it or leave it. He initially looks to play but then decides the better of it. Is late and gets a bottom edge to first slip.
Closer than the previous one, but wide enough outside off to be left alone.
On a good length, outside off, moving away, dabbed to gully again.
Fuller, outside off, a touch wider, swinging away, Rahane looks to drive but is a bit loose and gets a thick outside edge. It lands short of gully.
Landed on a length, wide outside off, Ajinkya Rahane shoulders arms.
Outside off, moving away, pushed towards cover.

Ahh... that one keeps coming in with the arm and then straightens. This is because Trent Boult has kept his fingers on the seam and not allowing it to swing. RP looks to go hard at this one, aiming for a big booming cover drive but the ball lands outside off, straightens, takes the inside edge and hits the pads.
Similar ball, perhaps slightly wider, this is an easier leave for Rishabh.

Indecision. Outside off, on a length, Pant looks to push initially but then seems to be wanting to hold himself back. From the front angle, it looked like he missed the ball. But from the rear angle, the bat was withdrawn well before the ball could arrive. So, in a nutshell, nicely left alone.
Full, around off, swinging in, watchfully defended by Rishabh Pant.
A length ball, around middle, Ajinkya Rahane looks to tuck but misses. The ball goes off his thigh pads towards fine leg. A leg bye taken. 150 UP FOR INDIA.

Review time! Jamieson reckons this is close. He feels this is hitting leg stump. Umpire Michael Gough shakes his head. Williamson goes with his bowler and takes the review. No bat involved. UMPIRE'S CALL! Saved by a hair's breadth! What a ball it was from Jamieson. He switched to over the wicket for this ball and got it to swing back in prodigiously. Rishabh Pant missed his flick and was hit on the pads. To the naked eye, it looked like it would swing down leg and Ball Tracking did not entirely disagree. Clipping the leg stump. Close call.
Full, around middle, swinging down, Rishabh misses his flick and is hit on the pads.

Gift from Kyle Jamieson. Brilliant from Rishabh Pant. Outstanding from Kane Williamson. Who says Test cricket is boring? Half volley, outside off, Pant leans and creams this through the covers. The ball races away off the turf but the Kiwi skipper dives to his right and makes a terrific stop.

Earlier this morning, Rishabh Pant was up for a chat. On being asked about how does he approach his batting, Pant says that he just tries to play his natural game all the time and keeps things very simple. Does not like to take too much pressure and keeps taking it over by over.
Outside off, coming in, left alone.
Outside off, Rishabh Pant reaches out and pushes it towards cover.
On a good length, around off, coming in, watchfully defended.
Outside off, on a length, angling away, left alone. Successive maiden overs.
Fuller, outside off, Ajinkya pushes this through the covers but Henry Nicholls dives to his right and makes an excellent stop.
Now comes the short-ball Test, around middle, Jinx ducks.

Another beauty. New Zealand's coach said that he wanted an extra 10 percent out of his bowlers this morning and he is getting it. Around off, fuller in length, Rahane plays for the inswinger but the ball pitches and then leaves him, going past the outside edge.
Nips back in a long way, Ajinkya Rahane walks across, looks to flick but misses and is hit high on the pads, almost around the groin.
Full, outside off, angling away, left alone.

Almost a carbon copy of the previous ball. If any, this looked to be going down even more. Pant misses his flick again and wears it on his pads. Excellent over from Kyle Jamieson. His figures read 16-10-15-2.
This one comes in a long way from around the wicket, fuller in length, Rishabh Pant looks to flick but misses and is hit on the pads. Going down leg.
Rishabh Pant comes in at number 6, replacing his skipper, Virat Kohli.

OUT! LBW! Kyle Jamieson gets his man. Big, big blow early in the morning. That's 7 deliveries now that Jamieson has bowled in this innings, which would have hit the stumps and the 7th is one of the most important ones, because it has the skipper's name on it. Full, outside off, Virat Kohli looks to defend but the ball comes back in a long way and hits him on the pads. Jamieson appeals and up goes umpire Michael Gough's finger. Kohli walks down the pitch, has a chat with Rahane and takes the review. That looked to be very close to the naked eye. Bat involved? Not as per the Ultra Edge. Now, the Ball Tracking technology. HITTING THE LEG STUMP! A tall man is always difficult to score runs off and when he can nip it off the seam like this, it gets even tougher.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Kyle Jamieson

Commentary.Commentary: Around off, fuller than the previous one, watchfully defended.

Good leave, that is on line. On a good length, outside off, angling in, Kohli shoulders arms. The ball then moves away off the seam, generating oohs and aahs from the slip cordon. India have been leaving balls from Jamieson mostly on length, because of his height. 56 percent of the deliveries he has bowled in this innings, have landed on the good length area. Only 6 deliveries he has bowled so far, would have hit the stumps. Maybe, he needs to be a bit more fuller.
On a good length, around off, watchfully pushed towards cover by Virat Kohli.
Outside off, wider, easier leave for AR.

And next, he gets a beauty. The ball is not too dissimilar to the previous one and Ajinkya comes forward again. But this one moves away slightly and beats the outside edge. There is more. The keeper, BJ Watling, gets a wobbly seam ball and almost fumbles as the ball dips in late.
Fuller, straighter, Jinx walks forward and drops the ball right at his feet, watchfully under his eyes. Perfection in showing how to play in England, with soft hands, as late as possible.
Fuller, outside off, swinging away, Ajinkya Rahane shoulders arms.
Around middle, angling away, pushed towards point.

Good running. Around middle, Ajinkya Rahane nudges it through fine leg. The man is more at long leg, so there is an opportunity to come back for the second which India do not miss. The stand moves to 61.

Ooohh...the big indipper from the big man. Comes in from well outside off, Kohli looks to work it to the leg side but misses and is hit high on the thigh. He does not know where the ball is and searches for it, looking for the single as well. The ball has actually gone back towards the stumps and Kyle Jamieson quickly rushes to effect the run out. But by then, the Indian skipper gets back in his crease and tries to stop the ball which has already stopped.
Fuller, wider outside off, swinging away, let through.
First run of the day. On a length, outside off, angling in, Jinx nudges it towards fine leg for a single. Moves to 30.
Game of temptation. Fuller and wide outside off, Rahane gets a big stride forward to reach to the pitch of the ball but lets it go.
Gentle loosener, wide outside off, Ajinkya Rahane is not tempted and shoulders arms.
Around middle, on a length, nudged towards mid-wicket.
Kyle Jamieson to bowl from the other end. 14-9-14-1 so far.
Full, outside off, a solid block from the Indian skipper.
On a length, outside off, angling away, Virat Kohli shuffles across slightly and pushes it towards Tom Latham at gully.

Touchwood. No, literally go and touch wood. The umpires have said, play will start at 11 am local and it will definitely start at 11 am local. But there is no guarantee how long will the play go on. The light is very, very marginal and bad light could come into picture pretty soon. The New Zealanders march on quickly onto the field. They want to get as many overs as possible in these conditions. Out come Virat Kohli and Ajinkya Rahane. Trent Boult to finish off his pending over. Kohli to face. Here we go then...
... GAME TIME ....

Shubman Gill is up for a chat. Gill says that India were in a precarious position last afternoon but the Kohli-Rahane partnership has calmed down some nerves. Wants the middle order to capitalize on this and get to 300. Is disappointed on missing out after a start but is happy that he could see off the first tough period. Maintains that his game is not dependent only on leaving balls but also on playing shots whenever the opportunity arises. On him using his feet to seamers, Gill says that he plays cricket in north India where conditions are more or less similar to what they are here. Adds that he uses this tactic there and used it here as well. On his dismissal, Shubman smiles and says that he doesn't think he could have done much about that, detailing that he was playing for an inswinger and Neil Wagner did bowl an inswinger but the ball pitched and then nipped away. Stresses that he was not pushing at the ball. On the advice given by the likes of Kohli and Rahane, SG says that the skipper speaks a lot with him and adviced him to play close to the body in England. On Virat Kohli completing 10 years in Test cricket today, Shubman Gill marvels at the way King Kohli has carried himself, becoming a pioneer for youngsters and taking Indian cricket miles ahead.

PITCH REPORT - The surface still looks a good one to bat upon and we can certainly see some footmarks. Shades of green here and there and that will interest the fast bowlers. The pitch as such looks a beauty, it is the heavens which could dictate terms, sometimes with the ball, but perhaps more with the mind.

2014. The year which changed Virat Kohli as a player and as a person. Virat Kohli entered India's tour of England with a batting average of 39.5, with 6 centuries under his belt. Good enough? Absolutely. But then, came a nightmare, in the form of a certain James Anderson. Jimmy found out a technical flaw in Kohli's technique and similar to how Stuart Broad tormented David Warner during the 2019 Ashes, Jimmy tormented Kohli during that entire tour, where VK struggled to buy a run consistently. Not surprisingly, India suffered defeats with Kohli not performing. The soon-to-be Indian skipper was morally down. He came back home, not knowing how to deal with this failure. Is cricket over for me? He thought aloud. Let's have a chat with the master. Off he went to meet Sachin Tendulkar. And after that psychological meeting, Kohli got transformed. Since 2014, Super V averages 59.2 in Test cricket, with 21 centuries to boot. Later that year, he went on to become the captain of India in Test cricket as well and learnt to accept failures. It is human to commit mistakes but not inhuman to accept them. Along with the good, come the bad and Kohli's acceptance and learning from those mistakes has made him a tremendous player.

20th June, 2011. It was on this day that Virat Kohli made his Test debut, against West Indies, in Jamaica. Personally, it was not a good Test for him, with Fidel Edwards getting him out cheaply in both innings, but 10 years since, that man has become a legend. And it is not just his class or technique. It is his temperament as well, to bounce back from adversity and also - fitness. Kohli has gone on record to say that within a couple of years in international cricket, he understood that whatever he ate, affected his body more than others. So he had to clamp down on strict fitness rules. Honestly, VK admits that the first three months were horrible, where he even used to collapse while running, due to the diet regime and even went to the extent of chewing his own bedsheets at nights! Well, the legend that he is now, Super V is giving oppositions sleepless nights. He would want to commemorate this day and this Test with a fine knock first and later, possibly a win for his side.

Discipline. Does the letter 'V' come anywhere in this word? No, it doesn't. But 'Super V' has mastered this word to the 'T'. What we witnessed on Saturday was a batting masterclass. 44 from 124 balls and factor this - Kohli scored his first boundary on the very 4th ball he faced. He did not score a single boundary in the next 120 balls. Amazing discipline. It was at that time that the Kiwis were finding their feet and Kohli decided to get his head down and grind. Other batsmen came in, got more boundaries than him but he has shown not only his own team but the whole world on how to play in England. You don't go pushing at the ball here or searching for runs. You wait for the ball to arrive and then play it as late as possible. Tremendous patience. However, from New Zealand's point of view - don't remember too many instances of the bowlers bowling short to the Indian skipper. From the stats that we can munch, there is a massive difference in Kohli's strike rate when the ball height is between the waist and the shoulder. Might want to test that out today, especially the likes of Neil Wagner and Kyle Jamieson.

Technically, it is Day 3 but practically it is the second day as the first day was washed out, courtesy of the rain gods. But on Day 2, thankfully there were no leakages from the sky, as we were able to witness the most awaited match in the history of Test get underway. New Zealand though improved after the Lunch session and they would not be too disappointed.

India managed to get off to a good start courtesy, Rohit Sharma and Shubman Gill. They put the loose balls away and were looking good as they raised a 50-run stand, before Sharma departed. Gill fell soon after and Pujara soon after Lunch. Since then Kohli and Rahane have looked solid and have managed to stay unbeaten till Stumps on Day 2. Overall, they will be happy with their effort.

On a good length around off, this is nudged to the leg side.
Around off, closer to Cheteshwar, as he taps this to the gully fielder.
Fuller way outside off, Pujara does not go chasing after this.
Shortish outside off, Pujara makes another leave.
Outside off, left alone.

There was an appeal for caught behind but it is turned down. A length ball, around off, nipping away, Kohli looks to block but misses and the ball takes the back pad and goes to the right of BJ Watling, who dives that side and takes the catch. An appeal from bowler and keeper, but the umpire says no. The camera pans to Kane Williamson but it looks like he is not too confident about this and does not take the review.
Closer to the off pole, back of a length, VK hops and taps this to the off side.
Three leaves in a row as this is again, bowled outside the off pole.
Another leave as this was bowled outside off.
Outside off on a good length, VK watches it go by.
Around off, nipping away, length ball, Kohli keeps it out tentatively.
First runs of the session! On the pads, helped to the fine leg region for one.
On a shortish length outside the off pole, Kohli again is not interested in playing at this.
Still no run scored in the second session so far. Length delivery outside off, Virat shoulders arms this time.
Drags his length back and fires a short ball around off, Kohli sways away from the line of the ball.
Way outside off, Kohli leaves it untouched.
Good length delivery around off, Virat prods ahead and keeps it out.
In the channel of uncertainty outside off, Pujara does not want to play at this.
Length around off, pushed to covers.
Around off, defended watchfully.
Length, away moving from outside off, CP leaves this one be.
Around off, defended out.
An outswinger way outside off, Pujara, who is yet to open his account, is in no hurry as he leaves.
A maiden to begin the second session! On a length around the off pole, this is clipped to the man at short mid-wicket.
Another pacy ball way outside off, Kohli makes another leave.
Fuller, but way outside off, no issues in Virat to see this one through to the keeper.
Another good looking shot but straight to the fielder. Around off, length ball, punched off the back foot to the cover fielder.
Fuller, around off, Kohli punches this one to the mid off fielder.
A length ball outside off, Kohli leaves as the ball dies on the way to the keeper.

We are back for the second session of play here. Virat Kohli and Cheteshwar Pujara are behind the boundary line, waiting to come out into the middle. Now, the Indian batters and Kiwi players come out. Neil Wagner to begin proceedings for the second session.
... Day 2, Session 2 ...

Right then. A very good session for both the teams as they have made some strides into the game, but the Kiwis holds a slight advantage, having snared 2 wickets to their name. Who will take the next session? Will the duo of Kohli and Pujara make inroads or will the Kiwis make the ball talk and run through the middle order? An interesting session coming up. Join us shortly for the same.

It was not all smooth sailing for New Zealand as their gun bowlers, Boult and Southee were struggling to find their rhythm and the Indian openers knew how to get on top of them. It was when Jamieson was brought on, that he started troubling the Indian batters. Kyle was the one who broke the opening stand, with assistance from Southee, who took a good catch and removed Rohit. Gill was sent back by a peach from Wagner and they ended the session nicely.

The openers for India, Rohit Sharma and Shubman Gill were tentative to get going but did not let the Kiwi bowlers have any sniff. They kept motoring along and kept attacking the loose deliveries, and respected the good balls too. Within no time, they raised a 50-run stand and it looked like they could survive until the Lunch break, but the Kiwi bowlers did not let that happen. Sharma was sent back by Jamieson and Gill, the other opener, was Wagner's first success, in his first over. India went from 61/0 to 63/2. Pujara and Kohli ensured that they see off the challenge until the end of the session.

This has been a cracking start and a first session to the World Test Championship final. After having waited an entire day to watch proceedings get underway, we have been treated to a session of cricket, where both teams have had their say and it is a session, which has been shared by both sides.
Fuller on off, Pujara blocks it out. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 2.
Length delivery on middle, angling in, Kohli tucks it towards fine leg for a single.
Down the leg side, Kohli misses his flick. Watling collects it comfortably behind the stumps.
Fuller and outside off, left alone by Kohli.
Fuller outside off, Kohli watches the ball sail through.
Good length delivery outside off, seaming away, Kohli shoulders arms.
Bowls it full on middle, Pujara taps it back to the bowler.
Shortish delivery wide outside off, Pujara is happy to ignore that.
Fuller length on middle and leg, tucked away towards mid-wicket for a single.
Length delivery on middle, Kohli pushes it back to the bowler.
On middle, Kohli blocks it watchfully.
FOUR! Classic Virat Kohli! Fuller length on off, Kohli leans into the shot and drives it through the covers for a boundary. He gets off the mark in some fashion.
Bowls it fuller on off, driven towards covers.
Shortish delivery on middle, Pujara hops and blocks it on the leg side.
On middle, Pujara blocks it out.
Length ball on middle, Pujara taps it on the leg side. He wants a single but is sent back by Kohli.
Good length ball on off, Pujara continues his leaving spree.
Way outside off, good seam moment though, Pujara leaves it alone.
Good length delivery outside off, shaping away, Kohli leaves it alone. Successful start for Neil Wagner. A wicket-maiden!
Fuller on off, Kohli pushes it back to the bowler off the front foot.
Length delivery outside off, Kohli shoulders arms to that one.
The skipper, Virat Kohli struts out into the middle. All eyes will be on him and he will want to impose himself early on. Surviving until Lunch will be the main aim, though.

OUT! CAUGHT BEHIND! Neil Wagner strikes in his first over itself and he is very, very happy with this. Good length delivery around off, nipping back in, forcing Shubman Gill to play. He went for an off side defense but misses. The ball gets the outside edge and it's a regulation catch for BJ Watling behind the stumps. Shubman Gill has to depart and both the openers have been sent back to the shed before Lunch.
Commentary.Howout: c BJ Watling b Neil Wagner

Commentary.Commentary: Back of a length delivery on middle, Gill hops onto the crease, pushes it back to the bowler off the back foot.
Starts with a good length delivery on off, angling in, Gill defends it watchfully.
Change now. Neil Wagner is handed the ball now.
Down the leg side, Pujara does not offer anything to that.
Bowls a yorker-length delivery on middle, Pujara pushes it back to the bowler.
Outside off, Pujara shoulders arms.
Fuller outside off, swinging away, Pujara leaves it untouched.
Touch fuller on middle, Gill pushes it towards mid on for a quick single.
Length ball outside off, angling away, Gill watches it sail through.
Outside off, Pujara shoulders arms. Another maiden for Kyle Jamieson.
BEATEN! Peach of delivery on off, Pujara decides to defend it but misses. The ball whizzes past the outside edge, into the keeper's mitts.
On a good length on off, Pujara gets a thick inside edge into the inner thigh pad.
Short-pitched delivery on middle, Pujara ducks underneath.
Back of a length delivery on middle, Pujara is solid in his defense.
Fuller length on middle, Pujara defends it on the leg side.
Fuller on off, Gill drives it well but straight to the man at covers.
Good length delivery on middle, played towards mid on.
Typical outswinger from Southee on off, Gill leaves it untouched.
Down the leg side, Gill missed his flick. The ball gets carried through to the keeper.
Outside off, left alone.
Length ball outside off, Gill mistimes his shot, the ball goes towards point off the bottom half of the bat.
Tim Southee comes back on. 0/25 in his 5 overs.
On the pads, CP misses his tuck away and the ball takes the thigh pad and goes to the right of the keeper, and lands safe. A top over from Jamieson, a wicket-maiden!
Around off on a good length, nudged to the on side.
Around off, dabbed to the point fielder.
A fuller ball around off now, Pujara blocks it out.
That's a good ball first up from Jamieson. Outside off, the ball seams back in as Pujara hops and makes a leave.

OUT! CAUGHT! That's the wicket they were looking for! Kyle Jamieson gets the important breakthrough. Bowls it fuller outside off, Sharma was leaving anything in that channel but not this time. He pokes at it and pays the price. The ball finds the outside edge and flies to Tim Southee at third slip. He does well to grab it with both hands diving to his right. Rohit Sharma walks back to the pavilion. Kyle Jamieson is pumped. He knows the importance of this wicket and the opening stand, which was looking very settled has been broken towards the end of the first session.
Commentary.Howout: c Tim Southee b Kyle Jamieson

Commentary.Commentary: India's wall of the last few years, Cheteshwar Pujara makes his way out into the middle.
Straighter on middle and leg, Gill hops and works this through square leg and comes back for the second.
The man is deep at covers, due to Sharma attacking that area. Outside off, shortish, this is punched to sweeper cover for one.
Outside off, no shot offered.
FOUR! Sharma is latching onto anything that is short and wide outside off. This time, he gets back and packs a punch through covers for a boundary.
Outside off, moving away, Rohit leaves it untouched.
Around off, kept out nicely.
Length and way outside off, moving away further, as Gill shoulders arms.
Slightly behind the good length and on off, Gill goes back again and blocks it out solidly.
Back of a length delivery around off, Gill hangs back and defends it out.
Around off on a good length, Gill taps this one to the cover region.
Outside off, length ball, the ball shoots up as Gill shoulders arms.
A length ball, around off, this is punched through mid on for a couple of runs.

NOT OUT! A poor review by the looks of things. A thick inside edge and New Zealand lose a review. Good length delivery on middle and leg, Rohit Sharma looks to defend but misses. Looks like the bat misses his bat and he gets pinged on his pad. Loud shout for an LBW but the umpire is unmoved. Kane Williamson takes a review. Ultra Edge confirms that there was a spike as the ball passed the bat. Sharma survives.
Outside off, left alone.
Good length delivery in the corridor of uncertainty, Sharma lets it sail through.
First review of the game from Kane Williamson! It is for LBW and Ultra Edge confirms that there is an inside edge. Rohit Sharma does not go back and New Zealand lose a review as well.
Width on offer outside off, Sharma does not chase after it.
Back of a length delivery on middle and leg, worked on the off side.
FOUR! Absolutely lovely! Shortish delivery on off, Rohit Sharma punches it through the covers for a boundary. He brings up India's total to 50 as well.
Length delivery on the fifth stump line, Gill taps it towards covers.
Steep bounce! Shorter delivery on middle, Gill steps out of the crease. He is taken aback by the bounce and gets hit on the grill of the helmet.
Woahhh, Gill was hit hard on his helmet. The physio is seen running out into the middle now, to have a look at Gill. All good to continue.
Good length ball on off, shaping in, Gill shoulders arms to that one.
On a good length outside off, Gill leaves it alone.
Good length delivery on middle, played towards square leg.
Jamieson is getting some extra bounce here! Bowls it outside off, the ball hits the deck and shoots up. Gill watches it sail through.
Length delivery outside off, left alone.
FOUR! Width on offer outside off, Rohit Sharma takes full advantage of that. He stands tall and slashes it through point for a boundary.
Back of a length on off, Sharma steers it towards point.
Length ball on middle, worked towards mid-wicket.
Outside off, Rohit Sharma continues his leaving spree.
BEATEN! Length delivery just around off, Sharma has a poke at it but misses. The ball whizzes past the outside edge into the keeper's mitts.
Outside off, punched to the point fielder.

What a comeback from Jamieson! The extra bounce saves Gill. A length ball, around off, jags back in sharply and bounces a little extra too, as Shubman Gill raises his blade and lets it through. Zips over the off pole into the keeper's gloves.
FOUR! Don't bowl anything short to this lad! On a shortish length, around off, Shubman Gill rides the bounce and pumps this one through mid-wicket.
Outside off, length delivery, Gill is untroubled by this delivery and makes a leave.
Fuller, but in the channel of the fifth stump, Shubman watches it go into the keeper's gloves.
On middle, dropped to the leg side.

DRINKS. India have started very well and both the openers will continue to take this partnership ahead. Rohit Sharma has been solid in his defense and cut shots, while Shubman Gill has been looking confident and is supporting Rohit well at the other end. The New Zealand bowlers continued to bowl outside off but Indian batters haven't given anything away. The Kiwi quicks will be looking to take a couple of wickets, whereas, this duo of Sharma and Gill will want to keep everything out of their way until Lunch.
Third maiden in a row! On middle, Rohit's clip finds the square leg fielder.
Good length delivery on off, Sharma plays this one to the cover region.
Around off, RS nudges this to the square leg region.
Outside off, left alone.
Well fielded by the man there. Outside off, short of a length this time, Sharma goes back and punches this, but straight to the man at point, who stops well.
Starts off with a length delivery, on the fifth stump line, Sharma leaves it untouched.
Colin de Grandhomme is brought into the attack.
Back-to-back maidens for the Kiwis! Around off, Gill is on his front foot and he pushes this to covers.
Around off, slightly behind the good length, Gill looks to tap this one to the off side but the ball takes the inside edge and hits him on his pads.
Closer to the off pole and on a length, Gill draws forward and pushes this to the cover region.
Takes a few paces down the track, does Gill, but seeing that this ball was outside off and moving away, he watches it sail through into BJ Watling's mitts.
Similar line and length as the previous delivery, Gill, again wants no piece of this. Leaves.
In the channel of uncertainty outside the off pole, Gill has no issues in letting this one be.
Around middle, dropped to the on side.
Changes it up and pitches this one full and way outside off, an easy leave for the Hitman.
Around off, length, RS does not want anything to do with this.
Slants across a length delivery across the right-hander, Sharma walks a few paces ahead, but does not offer a shot.
Boult with a beauty! A length delivery, fourth stump line, nips back in late but Rohit keeps his eyes on the ball and makes a good leave.
Slightly behind the good length, nipping in, around off, Rohit looks to defend but the ball takes the inside edge and hits Sharma on the pads.
A carbon copy of the previous delivery. 4 off Kyle's first over!
An away swinger outside off, no reason to play at this and Gill leaves.
Around off, blocked out.
Outside off, shaping away, Gill makes a leave at the last moment.
FOUR! Solid looking stroke from Gill. An inswinger around off, Shubman Gill presents a straight bat and punches this through mid on and fetches a boundary for himself.
Starts beautifully! A length delivery, closer to off, nipping away, Shubman Gill is tempted to come ahead and block it out, but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Bowls it fuller on middle, Sharma is saved by the inside edge there! He looks to drive it on the off side but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Change. Kyle Jamieson has been introduced into the attack.
Length delivery on middle and leg, swinging back in, Sharma clips it towards square leg off the back foot.
Good length on leg, Sharma tucks it towards square leg.
Length delivery on the pads, Sharma is late into his flick, the ball gets hit high on the pads.
Length delivery outside off, Sharma ignores it.
Touch fuller on middle, nipping back in, Gill tucks it towards fine leg for a single.
Fuller on off, Sharma defends it watchfully towards covers.
Outside off, left alone by Sharma
FOUR! Full and outside off, Rohit Sharma cuts it through the point region. Two fielders give it a chase but there is no stopping that. Excellent shot.

Overpitches it on middle, Gill digs his bat down and gently pushes it towards long off. Jamieson gives it a chase and dives to put the ball back in. He keeps it to three. Excellent effort by Jamieson as he saves one.
Length delivery outside off, Gill continues to leave anything that is in that channel.
Good length delivery on middle, Gill works it on the leg side.
Fullish delivery on off, Sharma went for a drive but gets an inside edge. The ball goes to the man at mid on.
On a good length on middle, played towards mid-wicket.
Length delivery on the pads, Sharma misses his flick. The ball hits the thigh pads and rolls on the leg side. He wants a single but Gill sends him back.
Bit fuller on the fifth stump line, Sharma watches the ball closely and makes a leave.
Fuller length on off, Gill pushes it towards mid off off the front foot. He gets three before the fielder gives it a chase and throws the ball back.
Length delivery outside off, Gill does not offer any strokeplay.
Fuller length on pads, tucked towards deep square leg for a couple of runs. Good over for India. 10 coming off it.
BEATEN! That's the length Southee will be looking to bowl! Length delivery on off, Sharma looks to defend but misses. The ball zips past the outside edge, to the keeper.

EDGED AND FOUR! A little bit of luck for Rohit Sharma! Fuller length delivery on middle and leg, Sharma digs his bat down a bit late. The ball swings away late and takes the outside edge and goes past the slip cordon for a boundary.
Good length ball outside off, seaming away, Sharma leaves it untouched.
Pitches this one full on leg, Sharma works it towards mid on.
FOUR! Rohit Sharma gets into the act now! Slightly short and wide outside off, Sharma cuts it through the point region for a boundary.
Length delivery outside off, Gill leaves it alone.
Back of a length delivery on middle, Gill confidently pushes it back to the bowler.
FOUR! Shubman Gill is so good on the pull! Boult drags his length back, bowls a short delivery on middle, Gill pulls it through mid-wicket for a glorious boundary. First boundary of the WTC final.
On a good length around off, Gill shoulders arms to that one.
Length ball outside off, Gill lets it sail through.
Fuller length on off, seaming in, Gill advances down the track and hits it towards point.
A length delivery around off, Sharma looks to block this out, but the ball takes the inside edge and hits him on the pads. Tim puts in an enquiry but the shake of the head from the umpire.
Angles in a length ball on middle and leg, Sharma looks to clip it away but closes the face of the bat early and the ball takes the outer half of the blade to the off side.
Similar line and length as the last ball, this time, Rohit is smart as he does not go fishing and leaves it be.
That's a peach! A length delivery, around the fourth stump channel, the ball seams away beautifully as Rohit Sharma prods ahead and looks for the defensive block but gets beaten on the outside edge.
Around off, pushed to cover.

Worked nicely by Gill this time. Strays and delivers a length ball on the pads, Gill takes a few paces down the track and clips this one through square leg. The man at fine leg runs across and by the time the man can come across, the batters take three.
Length delivery around off, gently worked to the point fielder. 9/0 are India, at the end of the 4th over.
Around off, defended watchfully by Rohit.
Angles a length ball across the right-hander, as Sharma makes a late leave.
Gill is off in a streaky manner! A length ball, nipping back in around off, Gill looks to push but the ball takes the inside edge and goes through square leg, for one.
Makes Gill play this time, does Trent. Around off on a length, worked to the off side.

What a delightful ball and a good leave too. A length ball outside off, the jags back in at the last moment as Gill raises his blade to let this one through, and the ball whistles past the off pole, to the keeper.
A length delivery around off, Rohit pushes this one gently through covers and collects a couple as two men chase the ball down and clean up in the deep.
Another good leave! Outside off on a length, seams away yet again as RS shoulders arms.
Fuller around off, Sharma plants his front foot ahead and pushes it to point.
Another length delivery, outside off, nips away from the right-hander as Rohit does not offer a stroke.
A good length delivery on the fourth stump line, Rohit hops up and makes a well calculated leave.

A good length ball, around middle and leg, Gill misses his tuck and gets struck on his pad. The ball goes to the on side and the batters take a leg bye, while Tim appeals, but this was sliding down leg.
A couple to end the over! A full toss around off, Sharma taps this through mid off with the toe end of his bat and collects a brace.
Fuller on off, RS pushes it back towards Trent.
Length delivery outside off, Sharma leaves it be.

OHHHH, that was close, but Gill makes it back in time, otherwise, he would have been run out. A length ball, around off, Rohit looks to block but the ball takes the inner half and goes to the square leg region. Sharma does not want the run, Gill is down the track, anticipating a single. Sharma sends him back and there is a throw to the non-striker's end as Gill dives back full stretch and comes back in. Well done by Gill to come back in time.
Gets it right this time, does Boult. A length delivery, around off, Rohit prods ahead and keeps the ball out nicely to the cover region.
Boult starts off with a back of a length delivery, down the leg side, swinging past Rohit and BJ Watling does well to dive to his left and collect the ball.
Trent Boult will bowl from the other end.
Just 3 off the first over then! A fuller ball, around off, Gill jams it back to the bowler, as Tim Southee collects the ball and mimes a throw back towards Gill, who rushes back into his crease.
This was better from Southee. A good length delivery, outside off, the ball seams away again as Shubman does not want to go chasing after this.
Loses his radar here, Tim. Slips this one down the leg side as Gill misses his tuck away.
Big away movement noticed here. A length delivery, outside off, the ball nips away sharply as Gill makes a leave.
Another length delivery down the leg side, Gill look to tuck this one away but he misses.

Wow, what a start to the game. Runs straightaway for Rohit Sharma and India gets underway here. A fuller ball, on the pads, easy pickings for Rohit as he clips this through square leg. Neil Wagner gives it chase as the outfield is slow and does well to pull it back before the ropes. Three taken.

Well then, all set for the action to get underway now! The excitement is palpable and the crowd seems to be voicing it out too. The Kiwi players are in a huddle, as Kane Williamson shares his last words of wisdom, before they spread out on the field. Rohit Sharma and Shubman Gill are the openers for India and they make their way out too. Tim Southee has the ball in hand, ready to steam in. Here we go...

We are ready for proceedings to begin. Both the teams make their way out into the middle and stand side-by-side. Time for the National Anthems now. First, it will be the Anthem of New Zealand, followed by India.

India (Playing XI) - Rohit Sharma, Shubman Gill, Cheteshwar Pujara, Virat Kohli (C), Ajinkya Rahane, Rishabh Pant (WK), Ravindra Jadeja, Ravichandran Ashwin, Ishant Sharma, Mohammed Shami, Jasprit Bumrah.
New Zealand (Playing XI) - Tom Latham, Devon Conway, Kane Williamson (C), Ross Taylor, Henry Nicholls, BJ Watling (WK), Colin de Grandhomme, Kyle Jamieson, Neil Wagner, Tim Southee, Trent Boult.

Virat Kohli, the Indian skipper, says that they would have liked to bowl first as well but runs on the board have been their strength as well and they will look to put runs on the board. On tinkering the playing XI based on the conditions, Kohli opines that they have gone with the same eleven as announced and the balance in their side is good and the spinners could have a go if needed. Opines that they need to be professional here and feels that their level of cricket in the past 4-5 years has been good.

Kane Williamson, the New Zealand captain, says that with the conditions around them, they will make the most out of it. Goes on to say that they have gone with four frontline seamers. Adds that India is the best team in the world and they are very excited to play them in the final. Mentions that BJ Watling has been a great leader within the group. It is a great occasion for him to play the last game. Finally says that they have been trying to qualify for two years and are fortunate to be here.

TOSS - The captains are ready. Kohli and Williamson march out into the middle for the all-important toss, as both the captains will want to win the toss, looking at the conditions out there. Up goes the coin and lands in the favor of Kane Williamson! NEW ZEALAND HAVE ELECTED TO BOWL FIRST!

The Indian coach, Ravi Shastri is in for a chat! He says that they were in the team room yesterday and were eager to start the match yesterday. Adds that they are all ready for today's play. Further states that the kind of attack they have doesn't depend on what pitch they play. Mentions that both the teams will fight for the WTC and it is above all the World Cups. He says that when it comes to competition, nothing beats Test cricket. Adds that nothing compares to play in a WTC final.

PITCH REPORT - Simon Doull is down for the pitch report. He is joined by Sunil Gavaskar. Sunny says that a new ball bowler would enjoy bowling here and there is a fair amount of grass on this deck. Doull says that the seamers will dominate more, also keeping in mind the overcast weather and opines that spinners might come into play if the sun comes out. Gavaskar feels that the batters must be very aware and careful, for the first 30-45 minutes and they should look for quick singles.

Time for take 2! We tried with all our might and collective prayers to ensure that we could have some play on Day 1 but the rain gods had written our fate preventing even the toss from taking place.
