Regarding team news, India have already announced their playing XI with Siraj, Saha, Vihari and Umesh missing out from the 15. They have a strong XI and they can certainly give a challenge to the Kiwis. New Zealand, on the other hand, will welcome back the players who missed out on the last Test against England but the question is who will they replace? We will find out.

The big day is here! Yes, you read that right! It is time for ICC WTC Final between India and New Zealand. After two years of hard work, we are down to the two best teams to fight it out for the coveted trophy. Both India and New Zealand have done really well in the ICC World Test Championship and it sure is going to be a clash of the ages. The weather is not ideal as there is rain predicted on all the 5 days and we hope that it stays away and we get a great match.
Right then! 40 overs remain to be bowled in today's play. The Kiwi players make their way out in the middle. Rohit Sharma and Shubman Gill take guard. Tim Southee to open the attack for New Zealand.
... Day 5, Session 3 ...

So the lead is a slender one and the Kiwis will hope they can pick a few before India reduces the deficit. India on the other hand will want to do it unscathed. Still, a lot of time left in this game for a result. The third session would indicate where this game is heading to. Do join us after Tea!

However, the star for the Kiwis was their skipper, Williamson. What a gritty knock he played, he hung in there despite losing partners. The lower-order did provide him a little support but one has to say, it because of him his side is in the lead. He deserved a half-ton but that wasn’t to be.

Shami and Ishant were top-notch. Especially the former. He really got the ball to move and created a lot of problems. They were two down when the Day started they were only two down but lost 3 before Lunch. At one stage it seemed like the Indians will be the ones taking the lead, however, the Kiwis counter-attacked after the break and a few handy innings from the lower-order meant they have got some sort of a lead.

That ends an outstanding bowling effort from the Indians. But the Kiwis will be pleased they have a lead to play with. However, when the day started, they would have had a bigger lead in mind but just like their opposition, they too collapsed from a strong position.

OUT! BOWLED! Two deliveries is what it takes for Jadeja to sum up the innings! Fires a quicker ball on leg, Tim Southee looks to guide it towards third man. He was late into his shot and gets an inside edge onto the pads. Unlucky for Southee the ball rolls back onto the stumps. New Zealand end with 249 with a lead of 32 runs. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 5.
Commentary.Howout: b Ravindra Jadeja

Commentary.Commentary: SIX! Welcomes Jadeja with a biggie! Short ball on middle, Tim Southee stays back in the crease, has all the time in the world, and muscles it over deep mid-wicket for a maximum.
Slower and fuller on middle, knocked to long on for a run.
Loopy delivery on off, defended on the off side.
Bowls it full again on leg, worked on the leg side.
Tossed up on middle, Southee is solid in his defense.
Fuller on leg, worked towards mid on.
Floated it up on off, blocked out.
Length delivery on middle, clipped to backward square leg for a couple.
On a length on off, Boult taps it towards covers.
Length delivery on off, Boult swings his bat but connects it with thin air around him.
FOUR! What a shot! Bowls it fuller on middle, Boult moves across and lofts it straight over the bowler's head for a boundary. Crucial runs for New Zealand.
Shortish again on leg, Boult defends.
BEATEN! Back of a length on leg, Boult looks to work it over the keeper's head but misses.
Very full and on off, it is hit to mid off.

NOT OUT! That is nowhere near the bat and the ball is also going down leg. This lands around leg and then spins in. Southee looks to sweep but it lobs of something to leg slip. India appeal and the finger is raised. Southee reviews straightaway. Ultra Edge shows a spike when it is near the pads and Hawk Eye shows it to be going down leg. Southee survives to fight another day.
A single as this is pushed down to long on.
No ball! Boult has overstepped! On middle, kept out.
New Zealand has taken a review for catch. Was there any bat on it? Ultra Edge confirms there is no bat involved. The umpires now check for an LBW. The Ball Tracker shows it was pitching outside leg.
Trent Boult is the last batsman to walk out.

OUT! RAHANE HANGS ON! Ashwin gets rid of another left-hander. Good captaincy by Kohli to bring him on. This is tossed up on middle, a lot slower. It lands and spins away. Takes the outside edge as Wagner looks to defend. Goes quickly to Rahane at first slip who takes it on the second attempt.
Commentary.Howout: c Ajinkya Rahane b Ravichandran Ashwin

Commentary.Commentary: Another one tossed up on off, kept out.
Tossed up on off, blocked.
Short of a length on off, Southee punches it off the back foot towards covers. Ravichandran Ashwin does well to put in a dive and stop that.
Bowls a low full toss on middle, Southee whips it to deep square leg for a couple. Useful runs for New Zealand. They lead by 17.
Down the leg side again, a bit slow this time, Southee watches the ball pass by.
Serves it down the leg side, Southee leaves it alone.
Slower delivery on off, Southee defends it well.
SIX! Southee can bat too! Short of a length on middle, Southee shuffles across and heaves it over long on for a maximum. India can't let this tail wag.
Kust outside off to end. Left alone.
This is quicker and it comes in from outside off. Blocked.
A single as this is guided towards point.
On the pads, it is worked to mid-wicket.
FOUR! Poor ball from Ashwin and Tim capitalises! This is short and outside off, it is slapped through covers for a boundary.
On middle, blocked.
Neil Wagner walks out to bat!

OUT! CAUGHT! Very rarely you see Kane Williamson play away from his body. His long vigilance at the crease ends. Sharma bowls a short of a length ball on the fifth stump channel, nipping away, Kane Williamson is tempted to play a cut and has a go at it. The ball finds the outside edge and goes to Virat Kohli who is standing at almost a third slip position. He won't drop those. Good captaincy by Virat Kohli to keep himself at third slip. Williamson falls one short of a half ton. The scorecard might just show 49 but what an innings that was. He battled through really tough conditions. He just being out there was extrmely important. Had he been dismissed earlier, the Kiwis could have well been bowled out till now. Also, timely wicket for the Indians. The lead is a slender one and they would now hope they can take the remaining two quickly.
Commentary.Howout: c Virat Kohli b Ishant Sharma

Commentary.Commentary: Goes full again on middle, guided towards point.
Fuller again on off, pushed back to the bowler.
Fuller length, angling in, Williamson defends it watchfully.
Good length ball on middle, Southee does well to hand over the strike to his skipper.
Short of a length on middle, Southee ducks underneath.

FOUR! Back of a length on off, Kane Williamson guides it past point for a boundary. That boundary means New Zealand is into the lead. Looks like Shami is tiring out but Kohli is persisting with him to continue his spell. Williamson moves onto 49.
Outside off, left alone.
Fuller length on off, a bit late away swing movement, Williamson drives it towards mid off.
Short of a length on off, Southee hops onto the crease and taps it on the off side. He takes off for a quick single.
Length delivery on off, Williamson dabs it towards third man for a single.
Down the leg side, Southee gets hit on the pads. He hands over the strike to Williamson of leg bye.
Quicker and full on middle, blocked out by Williamson.
Fullish length on off, Kane Williamson saw the width and plays a confident cover drive. But straight to the cover fiedler.
An inswinger on middle and leg, Southee looks to defend but gets beaten. The ball hits the thigh pad and rolls on the off side. The batters sneak a run of leg bye.
Short ball on middle, Southee sits under it.

DROPPED! Tough chance but will count as a drop! Fuller length on off, Tim Southee looks to loft it but gets the toe end of the bat back to the bowler. Ishant Sharma didn't manage to hold onto that one as he puts his right hand out to catch it. The ball hits the palm and rolls on the leg side. A single taken.
Short of a length outside off, Williamson slices it towards deep point as he plays a square cut. He gets a single.
SAFE! More fortunate runs for Southee! On the pads, he tries to flick but closes the face of the bat early. It goes off the leading edge over point for two.
Outside off, some gentle movement away. Southee slashes but misses.
Another bumper, Southee ducks under. Shami seems tired, this will probably be his last over of this spell.
On off, not the kind of zip on this one as we saw on the deliveries today morning. It is guided to point.
Back of a length and on off, kept out.
FOUR LEG BYES! Bonus runs for New Zealand. The trail under 10 now. A short one on the body. Southee got into a tangle. He looks to sway away but it hits the body and goes down to the fine leg fence.
Outside off, left alone.
Back of a length and on off, this is pushed to covers.
A single now! On the pads, this is worked through square leg for one.
Not off the middle but two! On middle, it is a length ball. Southee lifts it over the bowler's head. The ball stops at it nears the ropes. Two taken.
On middle, this is pushed to mid on.
Well played in the end by Southee! Back of a length and on off, it gets big on the batter. Southee does well to take one hand off the handle. It goes on the bounce to gully.
Fullish delivery on middle, Williamson guides it towards long on. Jadeja gives it a chase and keeps it to two.
Good length delivery on off, Southee works this one off the outside edge towards backward point. He picks up a single. 200 up for New Zealand.
Fuller length on off, Southee pushes it back to the bowler.
Fuller on off, Southee defends it watchfully.
Down the leg side again, Williamson misses his flick this time. The ball goes off the hips towards short fine leg. The batters sneak a leg bye.
FOUR! Shami loses his line here. Bowls it down the leg side, Kane Williamson clips it fine enough to get past through Pant to the fine leg fence.
Two to end the over. Southee is off the mark. A full toss on the pads, Tim works it through square leg for two. He was looking for a yorker but ends up bowling a full toss.
JUST SHORT! This is full and outside off Souther looks to jam it out but it goes off the outside edge, lands short of second slip.
On middle, kept out.
Again the inside edge saves Southee. He probably felt a short one is coming but it is full and on middle, Southee looks to flick but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Slightly fuller and on middle, this is pushed to mid off.
The inside edge saves Southee! Length and on off, this one jags back in. Southee looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Tim Southee walks out to bat!

OUT! CAUGHT! Mohammed Shami puts a full stop to Jamieson's counter-attack. Jamieson was looking to reduce the deficit as quickly as possible. He did succeed somewhat but Shami gets the wicket which was starting to worry India. Shami bowls a back of a length delivery on middle, Kyle Jamieson didn't connect it that well. The ball goes off the top edge as he swings his blade, was in the air for quite some time before Jasprit Bumrah grabs it with both hands at deep square leg. Very well taken by Bumrah as that was very near to the ropes. Kyle Jamieson was a man on a mission but so is Mohammed Shami for India. He picks up his fourth.
Commentary.Howout: c Jasprit Bumrah b Mohammed Shami

Commentary.Commentary: SIX! That is long! Good length ball on leg, Kyle Jamieson lofts it over long on for a maximum. The crowd is enjoying that. He is looking to up the ante.
Short ball on middle, Kyle Jamieson looks to pull but misses. A lot of effort for Shami to bowl a bouncer to Kyle Jamieson.
Length delivery on off, worked towards mid on and rotates the strike.
FOUR! Shami drops it short on middle, Kane Williamson picks the length early, pulls it towards deep mid-wicket for a boundary. Brings down the deficit to 32.
Length delivery on off, Jamieson pushes it towards point for a single.
Good stop in the end. Outside off, Kane lets it be. The ball wobbles away from Pant. He sticks both his hands to his right and stops it.
On middle, defended nicely.
Just outside off, once again, Williamson thinks of playing at it but righ at the end leaves it alone.
On middle, Williamson works it to mid-wicket.
This time he does though as he strokes it through covers for one.
Beaten! Length and around off, this one zips through. Kyle is beaten as he pushes at it. It won't be easy hitting Bumrah on the up.

DRINKS! Post lunch, India on top after Lunch. Shami has been excellent so far and removed Colin de Grandhomme too. However, Jamieson has come out all guns blazing and looking to score quickly. These two have began to accumulate runs at a better pace. India will be worried about that as if the two stay in there for a bit longer, New Zealand might well take the lead. An interesting passage awaits.
Good length and on off, kept out.

India has taken a review for an LBW. Ultra Edge confirms no bat involved. The Ball Tracker shows that the impact is umpire's call, as well as the wickets hitting, were umpire's call. The on-field decision stays.

NOT OUT! Impact umpire's call and wickets hitting also umpire's call! Good review. It could have gone either way. Top delivery too. Length and on off, this one lands and then straightens. Williamson is squared up as he tries to block. It goes past the outside edge and hits the back pad. A huge appeal but turned down. Shami wants it to be reviewed and Kohli does so. Replays roll in and it initially shows a spike on Ultra Edge when the ball passes the bat but the third umpire says no bat involved. Hawk Eye shows the on-field call remains.
Play and a miss! Outside off, Williamson does go after it initially but in the end pulls his bat back.
Another one on a length, Williamson plays it late and onto the ground.
Two more! Quite a lot of twos in the last few overs and runs coming a little quickly now! On middle, it is clipped through square leg for two more. Trail below 40 now.
Two more! On middle, this is worked through square leg for two.
Ishant attacks the stumps this time and Jamieson looks to go over mid-wicket. He plays a hack but it goes off the inner half through that region for two. Productive over for the Kiwis.
Away from the fielder yet again. On middle, Jamieson once again looks to hit it on the up. He mistimes it but wide of mid off for two.

Finds the gap again! So the intentions are clear here, Kyle wants to score quickly and it may not be a bad idea. Length and outside off, he looks to power it through covers but it goes off the splice but in the gap for two.
That is a wild swing! Not sure where that came from. Outside off and on a length. Jamieson looks to go downtown but is beaten.
And again! Length and on off, Jamieson strokes it through covers for two. He is hitting it well so far but all these on the up shots are difficult.
Plays it on the up again! On middle, it is behind a driving length. This is worked through mid-wicket for a couple. Good start by the tall pacer.
A short one to end on middle, it is tucked to mid-wicket. End of a successful over for Shami.
Another good confident shot by Jamieson but this time he gets runs for it. Three of them. Length again, he strokes it on the up through mid off, Ashwin gives to a chase and saves a run for his side.
And again, bowls it from closer to the stumps, it is the outswinger again but outside off, Kyle lets it be.
Well bowled and well left. This time he bowls it from close to the stumps, this starts on off and then shapes away. Jamieson leaves it nicely.
That is a confident shot to begin with! Length and on off, this is driven on the up but to covers. Risky to drive on the up on this surface but he did it well here.
Kyle Jamieson walks out to bat.

OUT! LBW! Shami is on song here today! Yet another wicket for him. Third so far and the second new ball does the work for India. Shami uses the crease extremely well here. Goes wide, lands it on off and then gets it to jag back in. Colin decides to play back but he does so outside the line. It goes past the inside edge and hits the pad. The finger is raised as soon as the Indians start appealing. India are into the bowling all-rounders. Still 55 away.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Mohammed Shami

Commentary.Commentary: Another one outside off, Ishant is trying to get it back in from that line which he is not able to frkm today morning. Left alone again.
Good leave! Length and outside off, it does come in a little but not enough to make the batter play.
Back of a length and on off, Williamson pushes it to covers. Not seen the new ball do a lot so far. Just the two in 10, one from Shami and the other from Ishant.
Gets this one to shape inwards but the line is down the leg side. Williamson looks to flick but misses.
Back of a length and on off, Williamson pushes it to covers.
EXCELLENT FROM JADEJA! Short and on middle, this is pulled hard through square leg. Jadeja runs to his right quickly, stops it, gets back to his feet in no time and keeps it to one.
Good length delivery outside off, left alone.
FOUR! Short and wide outside off, Kane Williamson works it past point for a boundary. India needs to be careful here. They should not allow leaking runs like that with the new ball.
Short of a length delivery on off, a bit swing movement, Williamson shoulders arms.
FOUR LEG BYES! Back of a length delivery on leg, Kane Williamson misses his flick. The ball runs off the pads towards fine leg for a boundary.
Short of a length, Colin de Grandhomme steers it towards gully. Rahane couldn't make a clean stop and allows a single.
Good length delivery outside off, nipping away, Colin de Grandhomme is beaten on the outside edge. Swing straightaway from Mohammed Shami as he bowls it with the new duke ball.
The second new ball is now available and it is taken immediately. Shami is also back on.
Drifted it on leg, tucked towards square leg. That might be Jadeja's last spell for the session as the new ball is available.
Fuller on off, blocked out.
Loopy delivery outside off, Williamson rocks back and punches it towards point.
Tossed up on off, steered towards point.
Shorter on leg, Colin de Grandhomme looks to clip it away but misses. He gets hit on the thigh pad. The ball rolls behind square and he grabs a single. Might have got an inside edge there.
Fuller on middle, pushed back to the bowler. He is not able to find turn at the moment.
A maiden by Bumrah. Good one too as he made Williamson play almost every ball. On middle, kept out.
Angled into the pads, Williamson works it to mid-wicket.
On off, kept out.
Once again, Bumrah bowls a length ball on off, Williamson lets the ball do its bit and plays it onto the ground right next to his body.
Nice and late! Williamson lets the ball come to him and guides it right at the end towards point.
Bumrah goes wide of the crease, he angles it into the middle pole, hoping for it to holds its line. It goes straight on and it is played to mid on.
Drifting on leg, Colin de Grandhomme clips it to mid-wicket.
Quicker on off, Williamson cuts it towards backward point. Gill does well to put in a dive and stop the ball. He keeps it to a single.
Flatter on middle, Williamson defends it on the on side.
Tossed up on off, Williamson misses his cut shot. A little bit of excitement from the Indian players but no edge though.
Fuller on middle, Williamson prods and defends it watchfully.
Fuller on middle, Colin de Grandhomme works it off the inner half of his blade towards mid off. He gets a single. 150 up for New Zealand.
Length delivery on off, blocked out.
On a length on off, Williamson is late into his defense. The ball goes off the outside edge behind gully for a couple of runs. 150 up for the Kiwis.
Length delivery on off, Williamson defends it onto the pitch.
Good length ball on middle, angling in, Williamson pushes it back to the bowler off the back foot.
Length delivery on off, Williamson keeps it out.
Fuller length on off, Williamson taps it towards point.
Fuller on middle, CdG blocks it out. A maiden for Jadeja.
Tossed up on off, pushed back to the bowler.
Quicker one on leg, defended out.
Slower through the air, pushed back to the bowler.
On off, tapped towards point.
Flatter delivery on leg, worked on the leg side.
Fuller on off, nudged on the leg side.
Length ball on off, Williamson is solid in his defense.
Outside off, swinging in, Williamson shoulders arms.
Good length ball on middle, blocked out.
Length ball on off, nudged towards mid-wicket for one.
Length delivery on off, Colin de Grandhomme pulls it towards mid-wicket. Ashwin runs to grab it but it's far away from him. Two taken.
On middle and leg, tucked towards square leg for another single.
Full and tossed up on leg, flicked through square leg for a run.
Loopy ball on middle, guided through mid-wicket for a single. Jadeja has overstepped. No ball signaled.
Floated it up on off, pushed back to the bowler.
Fuller on middle, blocked out.
Tossed up on leg, worked on the leg side for a single.
Ravindra Jadeja comes into the attack. Spin for the first time today.
Flatter and quicker on leg, pushed back to the bowler.
Good length delivery on off, angling in, de Grandhomme lets it sail through.
On a length outside off, left alone.
Fuller on off, blocked out.

Length delivery on off, Colin de Grandhomme looks to work it over mid-wicket but gets an inside edge onto the pads. He is pretty clear with his intent. He is going to play his natural game, that is to attack.
Fuller on middle, de Grandhomme pushes it back to the bowler.
FOUR! What a way to start post Lunch! Serves a half-volley on off, Colin de Grandhomme leans into the shot and drives it through the covers for a boundary. Lovely cover drive from the mullet man.

An important session coming up. This session could very much decide where the result would be more inclined towards. The Indian players hurl out to the middle all charged up, followed by Kane Williamson and Colin de Grandhomme. Jasprit Bumrah to continue the proceedings with the ball.
... Day 5, Session 2 ...

The Kiwis all of a sudden find themselves on the back foot. From 117 for 2, they have slipped to 135 for 5. Their skipper is still battling it out there but Colin de Grandhomme is new and it is not easy for the new batters to settle in. They need a stand. They still trail by over 80. Will we see a change in approach by them? Will they look to score freely after the break? One believes they just can’t keep blocking in such conditions. An interesting second session awaits. Do join us in a bit.

The session though did not start off in the best of manners as they went wicket-less in the first hour. However, they did not let New Zealand score freely too and after the Drinks break, it all changed. Shami, Bumrah, and Ishant all found their lengths. Shami was the pick of the lot as he got two out of the three to fall and Ishant has one. Bumrah did not have a wicket to his name but kept it tight. More of the same is what India would want.
End of a superb session for India! And their bowlers have evoked life back into this game. Yes, the draw is still the likeliest result but there is still a chance of a result being squeezed out.
An inswinger on middle, Williamson blocks it out. All smiles in the Indian camp right now. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 5.
Good length delivery on off, nipping away, Williamson looks to defend. The ball finds the outside edge but Williamson played it with soft hands, thus, gets carried towards first slip on one bounce.
Length delivery on middle, big inward movement, Williamson shuffles across a bit as he looks to hit it on the leg side. He gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Fullish length on middle, angling in, Williamson tickles it to short mi-wicket.
Length delivery on the fifth stump channel, Williamson shoulders arms.
Fuller length, bowls it straighter, Williamson defends it off the front foot.
Down the leg side. Colin looks to flick but misses.
On middle, this is worked to mid-wicket.
Another one on off, blocked.
Good length again and on middle, kept out.
Colin de Grandhomme is the next batsman in.

OUT! TIMBER! India on fire here! They have another one and half the side back in the hut for the Kiwis and they still trail by another 82 runs. This is a beauty! Too good. This lands on middle, Watling does nothing wrong as he tries to defend the original trajectory. The ball pitches and then moves away. Hits the top of middle and off. Shami is ecstatic, the fans are ecstatic. Game on. Watling could have put in a better stride forward. He was rooted to his crease there and hence, could not adjust to the movement. Also, brilliant from Kohli, he's chopping and changing the ends of his bowlers exceptionally. The last 3 out of the 4 wickets have all come in the first over of a new spell of a bowler.
Commentary.Howout: b Mohammed Shami

Commentary.Commentary: Big swing! Shorter and on off, shapes away. Watling lets it be.
On off, this time he blocks it solidly.

Lovely stuff from Ishant. Something about this Indian attack after the loss of Taylor. They have been hitting the right lines and lengths and causing problems. On off, Williamson looks to defend the original trajectory but the ball moves away and whizzes past the outside edge.
Watling is off the mark! On off, it shapes back in. Watling works it down to fine leg for one.
BJ Watling comes out to bat.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! India have another and the pressure they have been building has paid off. Nicholls walks back for a single digit score. He could have left that one. Yes, Ishant is bowling from around the wicket, it is angling into him but this was quite wide outside off. It lands in the 6th stump channel. Nicholls prods forward and reaches out for it. This one lands and holds its line. It goes off the outside edge between first and the second slip fielder. Rohit dives to his right and takes it. Can India get another one before Lunch?
Commentary.Howout: c Rohit Sharma b Ishant Sharma

Commentary.Commentary: Good length and on off, Nicholls guides it to point.
Just outside off, left alone.
FOUR! Low full toss on middle, Kane Williamson whips it towards deep mid-wicket for a boundary. He has been patient throughout and finally fetches himself a boundary. His first boundary of the day.
On middle, Nicholls clips it to deep square leg for a single.
Good length delivery outside off, Nicholls lets it sail through.
Fuller on off, defended with ease.
On a length on middle, Nicholls defends it watchfully. Bumrah has overstepped and will have to reload again.
Good length ball outside off, Nicholls decides to leave as he raises his blade. The ball gets off the bottom half and goes towards slips.
Length delivery on off, Nicholls blocks it out.
A good finish by Shami. Length and on off, shapes away. Williamson plays it late and with soft hands. Onto the ground.
Fuller and around off, Kane pushes it to mid off.
Another one on the stumps, kept out.
On off, this is pushed to covers.
Slips this one down the leg side. Williamson lets it be. Pant does not collect it cleanly but no runs conceded.
On middle, Williamson works it to mid-wicket.
A good maiden over by Bumrah! On off, it is kept out nicely.
Angles one across from the off pole. Nicholls left it alone.
Really good from Bumrah. He's attacking the stumps and creating problems now. This lands just around leg and this straightens. Nicholls looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pad.
Well wide outside off this time. Easy leave.
On the pads, Nicholls tries to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. Bumrah is really getting the ball to zip through nicely.
Bumrah starting to find his line and length. On off, on a length. Blocked.
A harmless delivery to end. Outside off, left alone.
Outside off, left alone.
On middle, Nicholls looks to block but it goes off the inside edge down to fine leg for one.
Angled into middle, it is worked to mid-wicket.
FOUR! Put away! That cut shot has been nailed! Short and wide outside off, Nicholls hops and cuts it over point for a boundary.
BEATEN! Shami is bowling with a lot of fire here! This is a back of a length delicery, really gets it to bounce nicely. Nicholls hops and tries to block but it goes just past the glove.
A bumper to end, ducked under.
Excellent! Makes the batter play again by landing it on off. Blocked. Williamson again plays it very late with soft hands. Perfect technique to play in such conditions.
Bumrah is starting to get into his element now. Good length and it holds its line from off. Williamson is beaten as he tries to play the original trajectory.
Loose! Perhaps a loss in concentration and since, runs scoring has been difficult, he just got tempted to go after that. It is short and outside off. Williamson throws his bat at it but is beaten.
Outside off, left alone.

All of a sudden there is a spring in the step of the Indians. That is a jaffa from Bumrah but how good did Williamson play that. This lands on off and then moves away late. Williamson is almost committed to a front foot defense but right at the end, he leaves it alone. Brilliant. He too is keeping an eye on the ball right till the end.
Fuller in length again but the line is outside off, left alone.
Solid! Good length and on off, blocked.

FOUR BYES! That comes in a long way. This lands well outside off and comes back in. Nicholls leaves it alone. It keeps swinging in and goes past the dive of Pant who had no chance and down to the fine leg fence.
Close! This lands on off and then comes back in. Williamson looks to block but it goes off the inner half through square leg for one.
Nicholls is off the mark! Angled into the pads, Henry looks to work it on the leg side but closes the face of the bat early. It goes off the leading edge towards cover for one.
Henry Nicholls walks out to bat!

OUT! Taken! That is a really good catch by Gill and India have gotten the wicket they so desperately wanted. The Drinks break does the job for the Indians and they are absolutely pumped up. A well-deserved wicket for Shami. He has been outstanding so far and he gets the reward. He lands it just behind a driving length. Taylor goes for the drive but due to the extra bounce Shami is getting it goes off the higher part and hence, uppishly to the right of Gill at extra cover. He dives and takes a sharp catch. Can India build on this? New Zealand still trail by 100.
Commentary.Howout: c Shubman Gill b Mohammed Shami

Commentary.Commentary: On middle, Williamson works it to mid-wicket.
Outside off, left alone.
Another one on a length, blocked.
Back of a length again, Williamson hangs back and keeps it out.
Back of a length and on off, Williamson defends it.
Back of a length and on off, Williamson pushes it to covers.

DRINKS! A solid hour of play for the Kiwis. They've gone about things slowly but haven't lost a wicket. One believes as the game progresses, they would start to up the ante slowly. India on the other hand, have bowled decently in bits and pieces. They need a wicket but who will provide it for them? We will find out after the break.
Another one on off, kept out.
Well fielded! On middle, this is worked nicely but the man at mid-wicker dives to his left and stops it.
On middle, Taylor hangs back and plays it to mid on.
Just outside off, Taylor shoulders arms to it. Not a lot of carry on that one as it goes on the bounce to the keeper.
Good length now on middle, this is played to mid on.
Back of a length and on off, this is played to point.
Williamson probably misses out there. It is really full and outside off, he is late on the drive and it goes to point.
Back of a length and on off, Williamson keeps it out.
Amother leave as this is once again bowled outside off.
A little too straight this time. Williamson looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
Just outside off again, left alone again.
Good take by Pant again! Just outside off, this one stays low. Bounces in front of Pant who grabs it well.
Good length and around off, this is pushed towards cover.
Beaten! That is loose from Taylor. Yes, this is there to drive, it is full and outside off but he goes after to away from his body with his feet rooted to the crease. Gets beaten.

FOUR! Was that a chance? Not really! That was a superb effort. This is on the pads, Taylor looks to flick but it goes off the glove or the shoulder of the bat. Pant moves to his left and then dives, does not get to it. It goes down to the fine leg fence.
Slightly fuller, this one comes back in. Williamson looks to push at it, it goes off the inner half through square leg for one.
On middle, this is worked to mid-wicket.
Angled down the leg side. Williamson misses the flick.
Ends the over with a harmless nut well outside off. Left alone.
Testing stuff! Just outside off. Taylor covers his off pole and leaves it alone.

Really well played in the end. The way he lets it go just shows how closely he's watching the delivery. Length and on off, Taylor initially looks to play at it but this moves away. He pulls his bat away.
Attacks the stumps again. Taylor keeps it out.
And again, hits the splice. On off, Taylor stands tall and plays it onto the ground.
The stumps at the non-striker end plays as an extra fielder there. Fuller and on middle, this is driven back nicely but it hits the stumps at the other end.
That one does lob to short leg, it does hit the pad but not the bat. Angled into the pads, Williamson looks to flick but it hits the thigh pad and short leg takes it.
This one is left alone but it is not a bad ball. It is just outside off.
On off, blocked. Good stuff in the last 10 balls. They are attacking the stumps a lot more and all of a sudden the two batters seem to be in a spot of bother.
A short leg in place now! India are probably hoping that one inswinger, takes the inside edge, hits the pad and lobs to that fielder.
Makes the batter play again by landing it on middle, blocked nicely.
Really good from Ishant this time. Gets it to jag back in after landing it just outside off. Williamson looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the pads.

Ishant hasn't got the radar right with the inswingers! He is getting prodigious movement but the line is on the pads. Taylor looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. Pant dives to his left and gets a hand to it. A leg bye taken.

Really good from Shami! He made the batters play almost every ball he bowled in this over and caused problems. Something Ishant and Bumrah weren't doing a lot. This one is the inswinger. It lands outside off and jags back in. Williamson gets an inside edge onto the pads as he tries to block.
Really good stuff! Making the batter play again. On off, blocked.
Extra bounce! He's steaming in here. Lands it on off and then gets it tot take off. Taylor gets hit high on the bat as he tries to block. It rolls in the vacant cover region for one.

FOUR! He does go fuller but is driven beautifully to the fence. That should not discourage Shami though as such deliveries can produce the edge. This is fuller and it shapes away from around off. Taylor creams it through covers for a boundary.
That is a beauty! Why didn't India start with him. This lands on off and on a length. It moves away late. Taylor is beaten as he tries to block. Shami probably needs to go a little fuller here.
Straightaway he gets extravagant movement! The line though is just outside off, it moves away further. Taylor pulls his bat out of the way.
Shami is on! First change of the day.
And again! Goes back to bowling one outside off, Williamson would leave those all day long.
Better! Length and on off, Williamson plays it onto the ground. He needs to be a lot consistent with such deliveries.
The line was right this time but the length is way too short. Williamson rocks back and blocks it.
Another one outside off, left alone. Bumrah just hasn't been at his best with his accuracy. Way too many balls outside off.
On off, Williamson plays it to covers.
On off, Williamson plays it nice and late toward point.
Finally Williamson scored his first run today! On middle, this is worked towards mid-wicket for one.
A quiet enquiry by Kohli! Down the leg side, Williamson looks to flick but misses.
On off, kept out.
Movement of the pitch! Length and outside off, this one jags back in sharply. Williamson fails to put bat on ball and is hit high on the thigh pad.
Another single! Runs hard to come by but that has been throughout this game. Good disciplined bowling by India so far. On middle, this is worked on the leg side for one.
Outside off; not played at.
Back of a length and on off, blocked.
And again! Not on the stumps, Williamson need not play at it. Quite a lot of harmless deliveries from Bumrah.
Pushed the batsman on the back foot on the last ball and now gets hit on the front foot but the line is outside off. Left alone.
A sharp short one, Williamson ducks under it.
First run of the bat today! On off and on a length. Taylor drops it on the off side and takes one. Ross is also off the mark.
Good length again and on off, Taylor plays it late and on the off side.
Solid as ever! On middle, Williamson gets right behind the line of the delivery and blocks it.
That is a really good take by Pant. A short one, a surprise short delivery. Williamson ducks under it. It keeps rising as it goes to the keeper. Pant leaps and takes it nicely.

Missing leg easily! Ishant though really liked it. He was pleading. This time bowls the inswinger but it is a little too straight. Taylor looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. It rolls on the leg side. Leg bye taken. Still a run to be scored of the bat today.
Ishant bends his back on this one. Lands it on off and gets some extra bounce. It hits the splice of the bat as Taylor looks to defend.

On the fuller side this time, Taylor strokes it back to the bowler. A very tentative push there by Taylor. That was pitched up and there was an opportunity to score but Taylor was probably worried about the ball coming back in and ends up pushing it gently back to the bowler.
Good length and on off, Taylor lunges and pushes to mid off.
Better! Bumrah needs to make the batter play a lot more like he did on the last ball of this over. On off, the length is also good. Williamson blocks it out. A maiden by Bumrah too now.
Gets this one to zip through but the line is down the leg side. Williamson misses the flick and it goes to the keeper.
Slightly shorter this time and around off, Williamson hangs back, plays it late and to point.
This one is just outside off, Williamson covers his off pole and lets it go. Haven't seen Bumrah getting a lot of movement in this Test. He's gotten good carry but not a lot of movement.
Angles this one into the pads, it is worked with the angle to square leg.
Again, really good carry for Bumrah but the line is outside off, left alone.
Gets this one to hold its line after landing it on off. Blocked. A maiden to begin with by Ishant.
Another one on middle, Taylor works it to square leg.
A lot better! However, not a lot of movement on this one. Length and just outside off, comes back in a little. Taylor plays it to mid on.

Straighter than the last two deliveries but not as straight as he would have liked. This starts on off and then comes back in. Taylor looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads. Ishant needs to start from outside off.
And again! Almost an action replay of the last ball. Another big inswinger but down the leg side. Taylor again misses the flick and it goes to the keeper.

Starts off with a big booming inswinger. Looking to hit the pad of Taylor who does plant his front foot a little too across at times. This one though is down the leg side. Taylor misses the flick and it goes to the keeper.
Who will bowl from the other end? Ishant Sharma it is.

Edged but well short. Soft hands from Williamson. Length and on off, holds its line again. Williamson plays it late and with very soft hands. It goes off the outside edge but lands well short of second slip. A good first over by Bumrah.
Does not find the gap. Bumrah goes a touch fuller this time and lands it on off. Probably looking for some movement in the air but there is none. Williamson plays it to point.
Now brings this one back into the batter. Attakcs the off pole again. Williamson is solid in defense. Bumrah has overstepped so first runs for today, courtesy a no ball.
Besuty! Goes wide of the crease and then angles it into the off pole. Williamson looks to block but the ball pitches and moves away. Beats the outside edge.
Well bowled! Good length again, this holds its line after pitching. The line though is just outside off, left alone.
Back of a length now and on off, Williamson guides it to point.
Starts off with a length delivery just outside off. Williamson leaves it alone. Bumrah gets good carry tk the keeper.

The wait is finally over! It is time for the action to begin! The Indian players make their way out to the centre and so do Williamson and Taylor who will resume their innings. It's quite windy and a lot brighter, for now the flood lights are also not on. It is Jasprit Bumrah who will begin. Here we go...
The news just keeps getting better! The umpires feel the conditions are fine and we have a starting time which 1600 IST 1100 local. Wohoooo!
Good news!!! The covers are off, the rain has stopped, the umpires are out for an inspection. It has also gotten a lot brighter.
The good thing is, the players are in their whites, so they’re probably expecting the rain to pass away quickly. Fingers crossed!!!
And the start has been pushed ahead! It is just a little bit drizzling but it is persisting and the covers are on which means we won’t be starting on time. AGAIN!

PITCH REPORT- Ian Bishop says that the overhead conditions are much lighter and this surface has a tinge of green which the seamers can use to their advantage. Mentions that Shami made the ball bounce from behind a good length and that is where they should look to bowl. Feels that India should also try to bowl at fuller lengths. Sunil Gavaskar adds that the rough which has been created by the bowlers will help the spin duo of India and should look to bowl a pacer and a spinner in tandem.

Rahane starts by saying he’s happy his family is here and got to spend time with them when they did not play for the two days. Also says there is a long way to go in this game, If they come on top in the first session by taking quick wickets then they will be in a good position. Adds it is England, anything can happen. Also says our bowlers have shown great patience and that's how they should bowl in England with persistent line and length. Praises Shami and says, he can really shine in the UK if he keeps bowling fuller and maintains patience.
Oh... here it goes again! Just as we were getting ready for the start of the day, the rain has made an appearance and the pitch has been covered.

Out of the two, the Kiwis have a more realistic chance of winning this. They trail by just over hundred. So if they manage to score quickly here, take a lead of around 200, then they could give themselves a chance of bowling India out on Day 6. India on the other hand, need the New Zealand side to collapse. Hope for a lead around 50, bat themselves to a position where they can’t lose and then try and bowl the Kiwis out on Wednesday. Now being an optimist, we still feel a result is possible, especially in such conditions where a collapse is always around the corner. Stay tuned for further updates.

Well, for those who feel, there’s not a lot left to play for in this game, it’s a certain draw and aren’t looking forward to the remaining two days. Let me tell you, there are just under 200 overs more to be bowled and there’s a chance of one team squeezing out a result. Yes, a draw is the most likeliest result but you just never know.

Hello and welcome to the coverage of Day 5 of the WTC final. First things first, let me start off with some good news - the weather seems absolutely fine for now, it is cloudy but dry so we can expect to start on time. Not only that, we can surely expect a full day’s play today as the forecast is also good. We here are really excited. Are you too?
... Day 5, Session 1 ...

3 pm local (1400 GMT) - DAY 4 HAS BEEN ABANDONED. Nothing surprising, we had the feel to it ever since that dark cloud passage came and we have it on the wall now. So two days lost then and two are left, to try and stage 3 innings, in say - 6 sessions and a bit more? The logical bet is for a draw now, but in Test cricket or cricket in particular, you can never rule out a collapse. Don't think any team would forfeit an innings in a World Test Championship final, else that also could have been a possibility, with either New Zealand or India forfeiting their first / second innings. Right. On that note, we take your leave. The forecast for Day 5 is loads better, so we should have plenty of action. Do join us then. ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

2.30 pm local (1330 GMT) - Okay. What differently can we write from the previous update? It is RAINING a bit harder now. Yikes. Seems like that should be it because whatever chances were there of today's play happening, seem to be going down the drain. Still, this is England and anything can happen. And now, dark clouds have come in to utlizie their free entry pass as well. That brings the never-ending issue of bad light too. The good thing is that the forecast is decent for the next 2 days.

Not too happy, are VVS Laxman and Shane Bond. With Day 4 also threatening to be washed out, that's two full days gone, in a 6-day Test. However, their ire is more towards the rules regarding Bad Light as both reckon that the ICC should let umpires take their own decision regarding the bad light and not just stick to one particular number, as is the norm. So you check the reading when the light is dim on Day 1 and then if it goes beyond that level on other days, even if it is bright, you have to take the players off. Perhaps, if the ICC tweaks that rule a bit, things can get better. You cannot do anything about the rain (unless you play at the Telstra Dome) but you can definitely compensate on the other days. Now, say if today is washed out, even with 2 full days' play, do you foresee a result? If yes, hats off to your optimism.

UPDATE - 2 PM LOCAL (1300 GMT) - Anything new? Nothing. The drizzle continues on its merry way and fans and players continue their long wait. There is some cricket going on though, as the Qualifier in the Pakistan Super League has gotten underway between Islamabad United and Multan Sultans. You can check the scores from that game but remember to keep checking this space too.

Ever wondered, if the World Test Championship had been held in the 1980s, which two teams would have made it to the final? West Indies would have been one for sure. Which would have been the second? England? Australia? New Zealand? Well, might tend to swerve towards the Aussies, but we may have different choices for sure!

UPDATE - 1.10 PM LOCAL (1210 GMT) - Welcome back. Those two words sound positive but unfortunately, nothing has changed at the Rose Bowl. India would want to have a bowl while New Zealand would want the winds to stop their howl. Jokes apart, it is still drizzling but the 'good news' is that we might just be 30 minutes away from action. The only thing is those 30 minutes are AFTER it completely stops drizzling. There is a lot of water just beside the boundary ropes but other than that, there is no waterlogging as such. Let's sing then - give me some sunshine, give me no rain... At least for 3 more days!
... DAY 4, SESSION 2 ...

We have some positive news this time! It has gotten brighter and the rain has almost stopped. The groundsmen are also doing their job. LUNCH HAS ALSO BEEN TAKEN! So let’s hope we have even better news when we return.

We’re back but with the same news! IT CONTINUES TO RAIN! The good thing is, there’s no puddles forming as of yet so we can probably start quickly once this rain stops. The question is, when will it stop?

Time for the action to begin! The players are making their way out to the centre. We are moments away from the first ball of Day 4. THIS IS WHAT WE WOULD HAVE BEEN WRITING HAD RAIN STAYED AWAY. For now, it continues to come down and our wait continues. We hope we come back with better news the next time.

Coming to the game now, have to say, the Kiwis hold the edge. The trail is just over 100 and they still have 8 wickets in the bag. However, if momentum is a thing, it is surely with India after they got Conway just before bad light ended the Day’s play. Virat Kohli would know on such wickets, things can change pretty quickly, like it did when India was batting. One can expect the Indians to come out all pumped up and we could well be in for an exciting session but not sure for now when play will get underway. Please stay tuned for more updates!

Hello and welcome to Day 4 of the World Test Championship final. Before everything, we know all of you have a few questions in your mind at the moment and those are, how’s the weather? Is it raining? Are we going to have any play today? Well, for now, all we can update is, it is raining, drizzling to be precise, the covers are on, it is heavily overcast and it does not look good. Now moving to the final question, judging by the forecast, it seems like we aren’t going to have any play today but being an optimist, keeping my fingers crossed and hoping for some action later on.
...Day 4, Session 1...

That wicket right at the end must have boosted the spirits of India. They really need to continue to make inroads as the Kiwis only trail by 116 and have 8 wickets in hand. They would hope conditions are a lot more favourable towards their bowlers on Day 4. However, the forecast on Monday is not promising with rain predicted throughout. We would be lucky if we get any kind of play. Fingers crossed. Do join us for all the updates. Till then, take care and goodbye!

In reply, Latham and Conway showed a lot of resliance. They battled through the tough conditions. One may argue batting wasn’t as tough as Day 2 but the ball was still doing a little. Both added 70 before Latham fell. Conway continues along with Williamson but he fell just before Stumps after scoring a half ton.
Their bowlers did the job in the first session and a half. They took the remaining 7 wickets cheaply and kept India to a low score. Jamieson was the star with a fifer.

End of another excellent day of Test cricket and one has to say, it is the Kiwis who are on top. They would have been in an even better position had Conway not been dismissed but they will surely be pleased with how they performed on Day 3.

The light meter is out. The umpires feel it is not bright enough to continue and the players walk off. Kohli is not happy but he has to. THAT WILL PROBABLY BE STUMPS! They can't come back on after 1830 local if they go off so the light has very less time to improve. Just as we write that, it is offical, THAT WILL BE STUMPS ON DAY 3!
Really good! This is on middle, Taylor plays it to mid off.
Excellent first ball! Made him play! Fuller and on off, it is pushed to mid off.
The next batsman coming in at No. 4 is Ross Taylor.

OUT! TAKEN! The bowling change has worked wonders and Conway is a goner shortly after getting to his half ton. Ishant is pumped up. Not the best of deliveries but he won't care. This is full and on the pads, Conway looks to flick. He seems a little early in the shot. It goes off the leading edge towards mid on. Shami moves to his left, stretches and takes a good catch. Can India get another before Stumps? They will surely have their tails up. This wicket will surely boost their energies. This could be a testing period for the new batsman.
Commentary.Howout: c Mohammed Shami b Ishant Sharma

Commentary.Commentary: Loose! This angles into off and then moves away late. Conway is rooted to his crease and he ends up pushing at it away from the body. Gets beaten.
Attacks the stumps and it is kept out by Conway.
Outside off, an easy leave.
Ishant Sharma comes back into the attack. His figures 11-3-19-0 so far. Replaces Ravindra Jadeja.
Back of a length and on off, blocked.
This is brilliant from Bumrah. Again, lands it on off and then gets it to move away. Williamson looks to block but is beaten yet again. Can't do a lot about that delivery.
Good length again and this one shapes away. Left alone.
On off, Williamson plays it to mid off.
Back of a length again and on off, Williamson is solid in defense.
Outside off, Williamson lets it go to the keeper.
Slightly shorter, this is pushed to covers. A maiden by Jadeja.
On middle, defended nicely.
Flatter and on off, it is pushed back to the bowler.
Floats it up on off, Conway pushes it to covers.
Tossed up on off stump, Conway keeps it out again.
Tossed up on off, blocked.
Once again plays it nice and late and onto the ground. Good testing over by Bumrah.
Relentless stuff from the last three balls by Bumrah. Good length and on off, Williamson keeps it out this time. He plays this one right under his eyes, nice and late.
Beauty! The pitch seems to have quickened up a touch. This lands on off and then holds its line. Williamson is beaten as he tries to block again.
Beaten! This lands on a length and around off, pitches and moves away. Williamson is beaten as he tries to block.
Slightly shorter in length and outside off. Williamson leaves it alone.
Fuller and on off, Williamson strokes it to covers.
Flatter on  off, Conway cuts it to point.
Loopy ball, outside off, left alone.
Tossed up, full and off, Conway looks to go big but does not connect well. It goes of the toe end towards the bowler.
Floated on off, Conway defends it off his front foot.
Tossed up, on off, Conway works it to mid on.
Loopy ball, on off, Conway looks to defend as the ball takes the outside edge and rolls to square leg for a couple.

DRINKS! It is the Kiwis who continue to dominate. Ashwin did get the wicket of Latham but Williamson has looked solid since coming to bat. They would hope they lose no more wickets before Stumps. India will want a wicket or two before the end of Day's play.
On middle, it is played to mid off.

Fifty for Conway! His impressive start to his Test career continues. Really good knock! Was shaky to begin with but now looks really solid. Gets there as he clips this nicely through mid-wicket for three.
This is quite outside off, not played at.
Angled into the pads, Williamson works it down to fine leg for one.
On the pads, Conway looks to nudge it on the leg side. It hits the pad and rolls on the leg side. A leg bye taken.
On the pads, Conway looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
Three to end! Conway moves onto 49. Short and outside off, this is cut through point for three.
On middle, this is nudged to square leg.
Another one on the stumps, it is worked to mid-wicket.
Another one on middle, it is blocked.
On middle, it is pushed to covers.
Tossed up on off, it is kept out.
Tossed up on off, Conway pushes it to covers. Jadeja starts with a no ball as he oversteps.
Ravindra Jadeja comes into the attack now. Replacing Ravichandran Ashwin.
A couple to end the over! On a length, on off, Williamson stays back and punches it through covers for a couple, before the fielder cuts it off.
Good length ball, on off, Conway nudges it to the leg side for a single.
Oh that was close. On a length, around off, angling in. Conway looks to defend but misses and gets an inside edge onto the pads.
A length ball, on off, Conway tucks it through mid-wicket for a couple. Good running.
Good length ball, outside off, Conway shoulders arms to it.
Good length ball, on the pads, Conway flicks it to left of the keeper. Umpire signals a No Ball. Overstepped.
On a length, on off, Conway defends it watchfully.
Loopy ball, on off, defended solidly.
Floats it up on the off pole. Defended.
Another loopy ball on off, kept out.
Floats it up on off, kept out.
Leading edge but safe! On middle, Williamson looks to work it on the leg side. He closes the face of the bat early. It goes off the leading edge but lands short of mid-wicket.
FOUR RUNNING RUNS!This is shorter and outside off, it is cut through point. Bumrah hares after it. The ball stops as it nears the ropes but Bumrah slips and hence, four taken.
One more harmless delivery. Left alone.
On the off pole, Conway stands tall and plays it onto the ground.
Back to bowling outside off but left alone.
FOUR! Nice and fine! This is way too straight. It is worked fine and it races away to the fence.
Another one on a length, it lands and then moves away. Left alone.
Good length and on off, blocked.
Flighted, on off, Kane Williamson prods and blocks it out.
FOUR! Swept away! Loopy ball, full and on leg, Williamson gets low and sweeps it through the square leg region for a boundary.
Tossed up, on off, Williamson guides it to third man.
Floated on off, Williamson defends it solidly.
Loopy ball, on middle and leg, Williamson goes back and blocks it out.
Flatter outside off, Williamson pushes it to the off side.
On off, Conway is solid in defense.
Outside off yet again, left alone.
Hits the length hare and lands it on middle, blocked.
On middle, it is kept out.
Outside off, left alone.
On the pads, Conway looks to flick but misses to get hit on the pads.
Flatter, on off, Williamson goes back and defends it watchfully.
Floated, on the pads, Conway flicks it through mid-wicket for a single.
Flighted, outside off, turning away, Conway leaves it alone.
Loopy ball, outside off, turns away, Conway has no stroke to offer.
Floated on off, Conway defends it off his front foot.
Loopy ball, on off, Conway drives it to cover.
Straighter on middle, on a length, Williamson blocks it back to the bowler with a straight bat.
A full ball, on middle, Williamson nudges it to mid-wicket.
A length ball, on off, Williamson defends it solidly.
That was close but not close enough. On a length, outside off, coming back in a long way, Williamson has decided to leave it as he shoulders arms, as the ball passes above the off pole.
A full ball, on off, coming back in, Wiliamson defends it to cover.
Good length ball, outside off, Williamson walks across and leaves it watchfully.

BEATEN! What a delivery. Tossed up, on off, Conway prods and looks to defend. The ball instead finds the gap between the bat and the pad and goes through into the keepers mitt's. There was some sound, but it wasn't off the bat.
Flatter, on the pads, Williamson tucks it to the leg side for a single.
Floated on, Williamson defends it watchfully.
Tossed up, on off, Williamson blocks it solidly.
Williamson walks out to bat!
Kane Williamson is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! And here comes the first breakthrough after a lot of hardwork by India and it comes through Ravichandran Ashwin. Loopy ball, full outside off, Latham looks to lift it over the short cover fielder, but this time he wasn't able to do that. As Virat Kohli leaps and collects it at a good height. Ashwin jumps and punches in the air in delight.
Commentary.Howout: c Virat Kohli b Ravichandran Ashwin

Commentary.Commentary: Flighted, full and on off, Latham prods to defend and gets an inside edge onto the pads.

DRINKS! New Zealand going strongly! The openers have got off to a good start but they will need to continue as it is not easy to start on this wickt. India know if they can get one, they can get a few quickly but who will provide that one wicket they so desperately need. We will find out if there is a hero, stay tuned.
Good length ball, outside off, Conway shoulders arms to it.
Quicker, on a length, around off, Conway defends it watchfully.
Good length ball, on off, Conway looks to defend but gets and inside edge onto the pads.
Touch and run! A length ball, on off, Latham stays back and blocks it to the off side for a single.
Angles in a length ball, outside off, Latham looks to defend but gets an outside edge as the ball falls short in front of gully.
A touch short, way outside off. An easy leave for Latham.
Tossed up, on off, Conway defends it off his front foot.
FOUR! Over the infield. Loopy ball, outside off, Conway gets on one knee and drives it over the cover region for a boundary. Well played by Conway. Moves to 38.
Flighted, on off, Conway keeps it out.
Floated, on off, Conway prods and defends it solidly.
Tossed up, full and on off, Conway works it to mid on
Loopy ball, on off, Conway pushes it to cover.
A loud appeal for LBW turned down. A full ball, on leg, Latham looks to flick it but misses and gets rapped on the pads. Going down the leg side.
A full ball, on off, Latham is solid in his defense.
FOUR! In the gap and safe. Good length ball, outside off, Latham cuts it uppishly through gully, but there is no man there. As the ball goes through the gap into the boundary.
Fullish on off, Latham drives it to cover.
A length ball, on off, blocks solidly.
On a length, on the pads, Conway looks to flick but misses as the ball clips the pad and rolls to square leg for a single.
Oh.. this time ball turns. Loopy ball, pitching on middle, the ball turns in. As Latham comes forward and looks to flick it but misses and gets hit on his pads. Down the off side.
Floated, full and on off, Latham keeps it out.
Loopy ball, on off, Latham defends it solidly.
Floated on off, Latham comes forward and flicks it to mid-wicket. Where the fielder dives to his right to make a brilliant stop.
Tossed up, on middle, Latham prods and defends it back to the bowler.
Loopy ball, full and on the pads, Conway flicks it past mid-wicket for three runs.
Back of a length ball, outside off, the ball bounces a little extra after hitting the deck. Latham shoulders his arms. A tight over by Mohammed Shami.
Angles in a lenght ball, around middle. Latham defends it back to the bowler.
Straighter, on a length, outside off, Latham lets it go to the keeper.
A length ball, outside off, Latham leaves the ball watchfully.
Back of a length ball, outside off, Latham works it to point.
BEATEN! Good length ball, outside off, coming back in, Latham looks to defend it but misses as the ball beats the outside edge.
Mohammed Shami is into the attack. His figures 6-1-14-0.
Outside off, this is guided to point.

Their pacers haven’t got a lot out of the surface yet but if you keep hitting the right lines and length, you will be rewarded. Will we see the Indians dominate after the break? We will find out.

The session started with the Kiwis bundling the Indian tail quickly and then it was onto their batters who have done a decent job so far. Not easy to play under such conditions but they have looked assured and scored whenever gotten an opportunity. The Kiwis will now hope that both the batters have got their eye in and they will hope they can cash in.

A good session for the Kiwis. Yes, they haven’t scored freely but they haven’t lost a wicket and it will get easier to score as the game goes on. For now though, they will be the one heading into the break with their noses in front but India not far from coming back in it.

The bowlers have now done their job and is onto the batters to do theirs. One thing is for sure, it is not going to be easy as India will be giving their all but they will need a special effort. The reply shortly.

The New Zealand bowling was outstanding. It wasn’t just one of them or two of them but everybody chipped in and picked wickets when needed. Jamieson though has to be the star as he started it off by taking the big wickets of Pujara and Kohli. After that though every bowler kept the pressure going and all the other three who bowled at least had a wicket to their name.

India on the other hand will be very disappointed. The conditions were really good to bat on and they have not lived up to the condition. Right from the start of Day 6, they kept losing wickets. Kohli and Pujara went in quick succession. Rahane fell in the same session. Jadeja went early in the second. Pant and Ashwin did try to counter-attack but they too were dismissed back-to-back and there was no fight from the lower order.

What an outstanding one and half session of bowling from the Kiwis and they are hands down the favourites now to lift this trophy. 139 is the target and they have to chase this down in just over 50 overs.

The second session proves to be another enthralling one where the Kiwis will be going for wickets whereas India will have to show resilience and character. Do join us for it.

He though then tried to counter-attack with Rahane. The two were successful for a while but then Boult struck. Pant though is still fighting it out there and India will hope he along with Jadeja can bat time.

What a session of Test cricket! Brilliant stuff! I did mention that we could have a clear picture of which way this game is heading after the first session but we were wrong. The game is right in the balance now, a few early wickets in the next session could mean a result is on the cards. A good session for India would mean a draw.

Direct hit and Jadeja was maybe home but you never know with direct hits.
The physio is out! Watling seems to have hurt himself when he was collecting the throw.

A length ball, on off, Jadeja works it to mid off, and takes off looking for a run. He is half way down the track, before Pant shouts NOO and sends him back. Meanwhile, the fielder lifts the ball and throws it to the striker's end. Jadeja is racing back to the crease and reaches comfortably in the end. But the throw is a little wide, as Watling does not collect it well, and might have hurt himself in the process.

Wagner and company make a loud appeal for LBW, the umpire is not interested and signals a leg bye as two is taken. We can see Ross Taylor from behind the stumps signaling to take the review, the Kiwis go for it. The Ultra Edge shows no bat involved. The Ball Tracker shows the ball was missing the stumps.
A huge appeal for an LBW is turned down. New Zealand review. Seems to be going down leg.

This is not looking good for India. Half the side back in the hut for them.

Fuller this time and on middle, Pant works it to mid-wicket. This is a good contest between Pant and Wagner. End of a good over too from the pacers.

On off, Rahane plays it to point.
Two more! On middle, this is worked through square leg. Wagner in the deep runs to his left, slides and keeps it down to two. Good fielding.

Solid! On off, defended.
Another run! For Pant this time! Angled into the pads, this is worked down to fine leg for one.
Slips this one down the leg side. Pant looks to flick but misses.
Sligjtly shorter in length and around off, Pant guides it to point.
Nicely played! Gets on top of the bounce of this short one and pulls it all along the ground through square leg for one.

Not the right shot there! Especially against Boult who is getting it to tail back in a little. This is just outside off, just a little bit outside off. Extra bounce too. Rahane slashes at it. Too close to plays that shot. Luckily for India Rahane is beaten.
On off, Rahane guides it to point.
Almost! Once again Pant is jabbing at the delivery which is just outside off, he plays it away from the body. He gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Wagner is fired up! On middle, this is defend back to the bowler. Who looks to pick it up but fails to do so. Does give him the stare.
Clever! A boundary is followed by a good leave as this is bowled just outside off.

Not a bad tactic from Pant but being attacking is different and being rash is different and he needs to be the former.

Good stop! Fuller and outside off, Pant hits it hard towards cover. The fielder dives to his left and makes a half stop. One taken.

Goes wide of the crease now and angles this one back in. A inswinger to follow after a few outswingers. Rahane plays it onto the ground.

A little too wide again, left alone again.
Fuller and outside off, left alone.

Pressure right now is on India. Pant needs to make most of the life he got and Rahane needs to play with a lot of responsibility. Can the Indians show character or will it be New Zealand who will dominate after the break?
Sensible! Outside off, left alone nicely.

On a length, outside off, angling away, Pant looks to defend but misses and gets the outside edge as the ball flies to Tim Southee at second slip who does not hold the ball cleanly and Pant gets and extra life here. Kyle Jamieson deserved his third wicket of the day. He has been brilliant.

Who will be the next one to come out to bat? It is Rishabh Pant who walks in at No. 6.

Pujara hangs his bat out tentatively, it goes off the outside edge and it is taken nicely by Taylor at first slip. It is Kohli's wicket which opened the floodgates in the first innings, are we seeing something similar here?

The wait is over then! Probably the most important session of this Test is about to begin! We could well have a clear picture about the result after a couple of hours. Kane Williamson and his side walk out to the centre and so do Kohli and Pujara who will resume their innings. Tim Southee who has two wickets so far will start off. Here we go...

PITCH REPORT - Simon Doull is down for the pitch report. Along with Sunil Gavaskar, who says that there is some grass left, but not as much as it was yesterday. Reckons It will be great day for the batters. Also says that a draw is the most likely result only if India don't lose many wickets in the first session. Ends by saying New Zealand does have a chance to sneak a win if they scalp qucikly.

Hello and welcome to the final day which is the 6th Day, the reserve day of the WTC final. Despite all the time we have lost due to rain and bad light in this Test, we still have a slender hope of one of these sides to squeeze out a win. The Kiwis have more of a realistic chance to win this game. Yes, a draw seems the most obvious result but an Indian batting collapse can’t be ruled out especially in such conditions. Saying that though, the Indians have fared quite decently so far. They have shown good resilience in difficult conditions but they will have to continue to fight. The first session or maybe even the first hour could well indicate which way this game is going. All to play for then. Stay tuned...
...Day 6, Session 1...

For the Kiwis, their chances of winning this game are a lot more than their opponent's. They will not only need to pick wickets but also restrict the run-flow. The reserve day which is Day 6 could prove to be an exciting one. Do join us for all the action. Till then, goodbye and take care!

In reply, India started off solidly but now has both their openers back in the hut. They lead by 32 and still have 8 wickets in hand. We believe they will try to bat time on Wednesday first, then analyze their position and think how to go about it.

The day was filled with twists and turns though. It was the Kiwis who started off nicely without losing a wicket in the first hour. India then fought back strongly and restricted New Zealand to 135 for 5. The Kiwi lower-order then along with their skipper counter-attacked and helped them gain a small lead.

A hard-fought day of cricket comes to an end. After its end, one just believes this game is heading towards a draw unless the Kiwi bowlers once again run through the Indian batting lineup in the first session of Day 6.

The New Zealand players are ready near the trophy, waiting for their skipper to come and lift it. Here comes Williamson and he does so. Very well deserved. A fitting end to Watling’s career. With that, the coverage of this Final also comes to an end. Hope you enjoyed our company. Cricketing action though does not end, there is a T20I game going on between Sri Lanka and England. You can catch all the action by switching tabs. Till then, take care and goodbye!

Williamson says it is a special feeling, he thanks Virat and his team and he is proud of the heart his team showed to win the game. Adds it is a huge moment for his country, he has been there for a short while but they have put in a lot of hard work and this will be celebrated and remembered. Mentions they do not have the stars but they have quality players and they held strong in this game and they had to. Adds no one had the upper hand for a long time but it was a really good last day for them. Ends by saying it was tough, they did not give them much and it was tough going but the batters showed a lot of heart and the lead was very important in the first innings. Finishes by saying Ross Taylor is always calm and it is good to be in a partnership with him. Says Watling is an amazing player, rises to the occasion when his side is in trouble and it is an end of a superb career.

Virat Kohli starts by congratulating New Zealand and feels they put in a massive effort to squeeze a result and they deserved it. Adds it was difficult to get momentum on Day 3, they did well with the ball but then the Kiwi bowlers did really well and put a lot of pressure on them and they were 30 to 40 runs short. Adds they need to have a fast bowling all-rounder but he feels this is their best side and had there been more game time, the spinners might have had more of a say. Also says Jamieson is a quality cricketer and is good with both bat and ball, he has the same attitude in franchise cricket too and is a really good player. Ends by saying this tournament is great for the game, Test cricket is the heartbeat of cricket and it is a great move and it is only going to get more exciting. Finishes by saying they are looking forward for the next series.

Kyle Jamieson, Man of the Match, says it is a massive moment in his career and to be standing up there is pretty surreal. Mentions they wanted to see how things pan out in the first hour, they wanted to land the ball in the right areas and see what happens against a quality Indian batting line-up. Adds it is good to have the ball in hand it is even better to get a couple of wickets. States he is pleased to get Virat twice, he is pleased to have spent time with him in the Indian T20 League and it was a joy to play against him here.

BJ Watling, says, he is proud to be here and to win this game is another feeling. States chasing a total like that on a wicket which was offering a lot was special. Mentions it is extremely exciting for the game to have a final like this in this format and he is pleased they got over the line. Also says his mom has been a huge help to him and so has his wife and his two boys, it is tough being away from them but it is all worth it. Ends by saying, the team has supported him a lot and he has enjoyed every moment.

Tim Southee says it sounds pretty good, and it is even better as we are crowned as the World Test Champions, with all the things going on the back it is a truly amazing feeling. Also says that, the two experienced guys in the middle, brought it home. Adds as an international sports person he would always look to improve in the future. Mentions this group of players are truly amazing and special. Says, Watling truly deserves it and he feels good for him as he ends his career on a high.

Ross Taylor says he is proud of the way the team fought. Adds Kane has been sensational. Adds this is a big highlight in his career and he thanks for their support and he hopes they have made them proud. Mentions it wasn’t easy to start but it got easier, the Indians never gave up and put a lot of pressure on them but he is happy they get over the line. Adds he is pleased he could see it till the end. Also says the 2019 WC was tough to digest but he is pleased they could win this.
They just needed to chase something under 140 in a little less than 2 sessions and they have done it in style. Their two most reliable players, Ross Taylor and Kane Williamson rose to the occasion.
Despite all of that, this game still seemed like heading towards a draw but a whole-hearted performance from all the Kiwi bowlers helped bowl India out within 80 overs.

Then with the bat, they went about things slowly, Conway set things up at the start with a fifty. There was a mini collapse in between but their skipper along with the tail helped his side take a lead. A slender one but still a handy lead.

The Kiwis are well-deserved winners one has to say. They won the toss on Day 2 after the first being washed out and elected to bowl, they weren’t at their best as India dominated Day 2 but they came roaring back on Day 3. From 2 down for around 150, they bundled India out for just under 220. Jamieson was the star with a fifer.
What a victory for the Kiwis! What a team! THEY ARE THE WORLD TEST CHAMPIONS! Just unbelievable, after all the rain and all the time we lost, a result has still been possible. Absolutely brilliant!

The final session of the day is underway! The Indian players are in a huddle near the ropes, as the skipper has his last say. While, Tom Latham and Devon Conway stride in the middle with their blades. It is Bumrah who removes his cap, so he will be starting with the ball.
...Day 6, Session 3...

India on the other hand, need a magic spell from someone. They need wickets and quickly. Containing won’t help as one believes if New Zealand play till the end, they will win it. Do they have a hero in them? Something tells me there is still a twist left in this game. Stay tuned.

Coming to the session now I really don’t think I need to mention who this belongs to. After bundling the lower and the middle order quickly, their batters have started off nicely. Their aim would have been to not lose a wicket as they have done so. They just need to continue to bat sensibly and they’ll be over the line.
So, the Kiwis have gotten through the nervy period unscathed and have also managed to reduce the deficit from 19. They now need another 120 runs in 45 overs.
